al]] (1), [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]] (1), [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Independiente|Independiente]] (1)\n|[[Club Atl\u00e9tico Independiente|Independiente]] (1), [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Lan\u00fas|Lan\u00fas]] (1)\n|-\n|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Brazil]]\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|2\n|[[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]] (1), [[Club Athletico Paranaense|Athletico Paranaense]] (1)\n|[[S\u00e3o Paulo FC|S\u00e3o Paulo]] (1), [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Chapecoense de Futebol|Chapecoense]] (1)\n|-\n|{{flagicon|COL}} [[Colombia]]\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|0\n|[[Independiente Santa Fe|Santa Fe]] (1)\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ECU}} [[Ecuador]]\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|1\n|\n|[[Liga Deportiva Universitaria de Quito|LDU Quito]] (1)\n|-\n|{{flagicon|CHI}} [[Chile]]\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|1\n|\n|[[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]] (1)\n|}\nAgribank cup\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! nations!! Times won !! Times runner-up !! Winning clubs!! Runners-up\n|-\n| [[Vietnam]] || || ||  || \n|-\n| [[ecuador]] ||  ||  ||  || \n|}\n\n|\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121016074446/http://www.j-league.or.jp/surugacs/ Official J. League website] {{in lang|ja}}\n* [http://www.jfa.jp/match/suruga/ Official JFA website] {{in lang|ja}}\n* [http://www.conmebol.com/es/copa-suruga-bank Official CONMEBOL website]\n\n{{J.League Cup / Copa Sudamericana Championship}}\n{{South American Football}}\n{{J. League competitions}}\n\n[[Category:Suruga Bank Championship| ]]\n[[Category:International club association football competitions hosted by Japan]]\n[[Category:CONMEBOL club competitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football tournament\n|name                =J.League Cup / Copa Sudamericana Championship\n|logo                =\n|caption             =\n|founded             ={{Start date and age|2008}}\n|region              =South America ([[CONMEBOL]]) and Japan ([[Japan Football Association|JFA]])\n|number of teams     =2\n|current champions   ={{nowrap|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Club Athletico Paranaense|Athletico Paranaense]] (1st title)}} \n|most successful club={{nowrap|{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Kashima Antlers]] (2 titles)}} \n|broadcasters        = [[Fox Sports (Latin America)]] (until 2018)<br>[[DirecTV|DirecTV Sports]] (South America) (from 2019)<br>[[ESPN Brasil]] (from 2019)<br>[[Fuji TV]] (Japan)\n|current             = [[2019 J.League Cup / Copa Sudamericana Championship]]\n}}\n\nThe '''J.League Cup / Copa Sudamericana Championship''' is an annual intercontinental [[association football|football]] match held in [[Japan]], contested by the reigning champions of the [[J.League Cup]] and the [[Copa Sudamericana]].\n\nThe tournament was previously officially called the ''Suruga Bank Championship'' between 2008 and 2018 as it was sponsored by Suruga Bank. Since 2019, it is officially called the ''J. League YBC Levain Cup / CONMEBOL Sudamericana Championship Final'', using the official names of the two qualifying tournaments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jfa.jp/eng/match/j_conmebol_2019/|title=J.LEAGUE YBC LEVAIN CUP / CONMEBOL SUDAMERICANA Championship Final|publisher=Japan Football Association}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe J.League Cup / Copa Sudamericana Championship was established in early 2008 by the [[Japan Football Association]] (JFA), [[CONMEBOL]], and [[J. League]], and sponsored by Suruga Bank in Japan. The championship is hosted annually at the [[J. League Cup]] champion's home stadium.\n\nThe first match was played on July 30, 2008 at [[Nagai Stadium]] in [[Osaka]] where Argentina's [[Arsenal de Sarand\u00ed|Arsenal]] defeated Japan's [[Gamba Osaka]] by 1\u20130.\n\n==Finals==\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" width=100%\n!Season\n!Country\n!Winner\n!Score\n!Runner-up\n!Country\n!Venue\n!Attendance\n|-\n|align=center|[[2008 Suruga Bank Championship|2008]]\n|{{flag|ARG}}\n|[[Arsenal de Sarand\u00ed|Arsenal]]\n|align=center|1\u20130\n|[[Gamba Osaka]]\n|{{flag|JPN}}\n|[[