2 September 2015|title=Electric mobility: the technology of electric cars \u2013 Volkswagen|website=Emobility.volkswagen.com|accessdate=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| [[Volkswagen e-Up!|e-up!]]\n| [[File:VW e-up! at Hannover Messe.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|-\n| [[Volkswagen e-Golf|e-Golf]]\n| [[File:VW e-Golf LA Auto Show 2013.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|}\n\n===R models===\n{{See also|Volkswagen R}}\nR models are exotic and sport vehicles.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| [[Volkswagen Golf Mk6#Golf R|Golf R]]\n| [[File:2017 Volkswagen Golf R TSi S-A facelift 2.0.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n| Small sports car\n|\n* Hatchback\n|}\n\n==Historic models==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen K\u00fcbelwagen|K\u00fcbelwagen]]\n|[[File:VW Kuebelwagen 1.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1940\u20131945\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Schwimmwagen|Schwimmwagen]]\n|[[File:VW Schwimmwagen 1.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1942\u20131944\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Type 1|Sedan, \"Beetle, Bug\"]]\n|[[File:VW Oval 1957.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1938\u20132003\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Karmann Ghia|Karmann Ghia]]\n|[[File:MarignyMay07KarmannGhiaFrontSide.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1955\u20131974\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Type 3|1500/1600]]\n|[[File:VW Typ 3 front 20080227.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1961\u20131973\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen 181|181]]\n|[[File:Vw 181 v sst.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1969\u20131983\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Country Buggy|Country Buggy]]\n|[[File:Volkswagen Country Buggy.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1967\u20131969\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen 411|411]]\n|[[File:Volkswagen 411 Front view Essex.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1968\u20131972\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen K70|K70]]\n|[[File:1971 VW K70 L Front.JPG|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1970\u20131974\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen 412|412]]\n|[[File:Typ 4 412 Variant aus Offenbach.JPG|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1972\u20131974\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Scirocco|Scirocco]]\n|[[File:1974 VOLKSWAGEN SCIROCCO.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1974\u20131981\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Derby|Derby]]\n|[[File:VW Derby CL front.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1977\u20131981\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Corrado|Corrado]]\n|[[File:VW Corrado 16 V (2010-04-12) ret2.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1988\u20131995\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Lupo|Lupo]]\n|[[File:2002 Volkswagen Lupo E 1.0 Front (1).jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1998\u20132004\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen New Beetle|New Beetle]]\n|[[File:2006 Volkswagen New Beetle Luna 1.6 Front.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|1998\u20132010\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Golf Plus|Golf +]]\n|[[File:VW Golf Plus 2.0 TDI Facelift front-1 20100710.jpg|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|2004\u20132009\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Routan|Routan]]\n|[[File:2009 Volkswagen Routan SE.jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|2009\u20132013\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Eos|Eos]]\n|[[File:2012 Volkswagen Eos -- 04-01-2011 1.jpg|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|2006\u20132015\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen Phaeton|Phaeton]]\n|[[File:VW Phaeton 3.0 V6 TDI 4MOTION (2. Facelift) \u2013 Frontansicht, 10. August 2011, D\u00fcsseldorf.jpg|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|2003\u20132016\n|-\n|[[Volkswagen CC|CC]]\n|[[File:Volkswagen Passat CC 2.0 TSi 2010 (14168908053).jpg|centre|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|2008\u20132017\n|-\n| [[Volkswagen Scirocco|Scirocco]]\n| [[File:2015 Volkswagen Scirocco GT BlueMotion Tech 2.0.jpg|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n|2008\u20132017\n|-\n| [[Volkswagen Beetle (A5)|Beetle]]\n| [[File:2012 Volkswagen Beetle -- NHTSA 2.jpg|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n| 2011-2019\n|}\n\n==Electric and alternative fuel vehicles==\n\n===Pure ethanol vehicles===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F053242-0034, Hannover, Messe.jpg|thumb|right| VW pure [[ethanol fuel|ethanol]] prototype car developed by [[Volkswagen do Brasil]] in 1978.]]\n\n[[Volkswagen do Brasil]] produced and sold pure ethanol-powered ([[Common ethanol fuel mixtures#E100|E100 only]]) vehicles in Brazil, and production was discontinued only after they were supplanted by more modern [[flexible-fuel vehicle|Flex Fuel]] technology. As a response to the [[1973 oil crisis]], the Brazilian government began promoting bioethanol as a fuel, and the [[Pro-\u00c1lcool|National Alcohol Program]] -''Pr\u00f3-\u00c1lcool''- ({{lang-pt|Programa Nacional do \u00c1lcool}}) was launched in 1975.<ref name=\"Bastos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.energytribune.com/articles.cfm?aid=534 |author=Milton Briquet Bastos |title=Brazil's Ethanol Program \u2013 An Insider's View |work=Energy Tribune |date=20 June 2007 |accessdate=14 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710193215/http://www.energytribune.com/articles.cfm?aid=534 |archivedate=10 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"Veja1979\" /><ref name=\"SeatleT\" /> Compelled by the [[1979 energy crisis]], and after development and testing with government fleets by the [[Brazilian General Command for Aerospace Technology|CTA]] at [[S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 dos Campos]], and further testing of several prototypes developed by the four local carmakers, including Volkswagen do Brasil, pure ethanol vehicles were launched in the Brazilian market.<ref name=\"Bastos\" /><ref name=\"Veja1979\">{{cite web |url=http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/exclusivo/petroleo/130679.html |title=O petr\u00f3leo da cana |author=Revista Veja |publisher=[[Editora Abril]] |date=13 June 1979 |accessdate=29 November 2008 |language=Portuguese |authorlink=Revista Veja |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006165850/http://veja.abril.com.br/idade/exclusivo/petroleo/130679.html |archivedate=6 October 2008  }}</ref> Gasoline engines were modified to support [[hydrous]] ethanol characteristics and changes included [[compression ratio]], amount of fuel injected, replacement of materials that would get corroded by the contact with ethanol, use of colder [[spark plugs]] suitable for dissipating heat due to higher flame temperatures, and an auxiliary cold-start system that injects gasoline from a small tank in the engine compartment to help starting when cold. Within six years, around 75% of all Brazilian passenger cars were manufactured with ethanol engines.<ref name=\"Bastos\" /><ref name=\"Lemos\">{{cite web | url=http://www.icis.com/Articles/2007/02/12/4500680/the-brazilian-ethanol-model.html | author=William Lemos | title=The Brazilian ethanol model | publisher=ICIS news | date=5 February 2007 | accessdate=14 August 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009164617/http://www.icis.com/Articles/2007/02/12/4500680/the-brazilian-ethanol-model.html | archive-date=9 October 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nProduction and sales of pure ethanol vehicles tumbled beginning in 1987 owing to several factors, including a sharp decline in gasoline prices as a result of the [[1980s oil glut]], and high sugar prices in the world market, shifting sugarcane ethanol production from fuel to sugar. By mid-1989, a shortage of ethanol fuel supply in the local market left thousands of vehicles in line at gas stations or out of fuel in their garages, forcing consumers to abandon ethanol vehicles.<ref name=\"SeatleT\">{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002339093_brazilfuel17.html |work=The Seattle Times |title=Brazil's ethanol effort helping lead to oil self-sufficiency |author=Marla Dickerson |date=17 June 2005 |accessdate=29 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227203948/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002339093_brazilfuel17.html |archivedate=27 December 2008 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"Veja1989\">{{cite web|url=http://veja.abril.com.br/arquivo_veja/capa_24051989.shtml |title=Um sonho corro\u00eddo |author=Revista Veja |publisher=[[Editora Abril]] |date=24 May 1989 |accessdate=29 November 2008 |language=Portuguese |authorlink=Revista Veja |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208192704/http://veja.abril.com.br/arquivo_veja/capa_24051989.shtml |archivedate=8 February 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Flexible-fuel vehicles===\n[[File:Brazilian 2003 VW Gol 1.6 Total Flex.jpg|thumb|right]]\n\nThe 2003 [[Volkswagen Gol|VW Gol 1.6 Total Flex]] was the first full flexible-fuel vehicle launched in Brazil, capable of running on any blend of gasoline and [[Common ethanol fuel mixtures#E100|E100]]. In March of that year, on its fiftieth anniversary, [[Volkswagen do Brasil]] launched in the local market the [[Volkswagen Gol|Gol]] 1.6 Total Flex, the first Brazilian commercial [[flexible fuel vehicle]] capable of running on any mix of [[E20 fuel|E20-E25]] gasoline and up to 100% [[hydrous]] ethanol fuel ([[Common ethanol fuel mixtures#E100|E100]]).<ref name=\"SusEthanol\">{{Cite book|author1=Goettemoeller, Jeffrey |author2=Adrian Goettemoeller | title = Sustainable Ethanol: Biofuels, Biorefineries, Cellulosic Biomass, Flex-Fuel Vehicles, and Sustainable Farming for Energy Independence | year = 2007| publisher=Prairie Oak Publishing, Maryville, Missouri |pages=56\u201361 | isbn=978-0-9786293-0-4}}</ref><ref name=\"autonews.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060323/REUTERS/60323043/1111 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213023830/http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20060323%2FREUTERS%2F60323043%2F1111 |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 February 2009 |title=Volkswagen to stop making gas-only cars for Brazil |newspaper=Automotive News |date=23 March 2006 |accessdate=18 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vwbr.com.br/VWBrasil/Historia/A-nova-Volkswagen.aspx |title=A Nova Volkswagen |publisher=Volkswagen do Brasil |accessdate=18 October 2008 |language=Portuguese |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915184129/http://www.vwbr.com.br/VWBrasil/Historia/A-nova-Volkswagen.aspx <!--Added by H3llBot--> |archivedate=15 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parana-online.com.br/canal/automoveis/news/170341/ |title=Volkswagen lan\u00e7a Golf Total Flex 1.6 |publisher=ParanaOnline |date=30 March 2006 |accessdate=18 October 2008 |language=Portuguese |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522121038/http://www.parana-online.com.br/canal/automoveis/news/170341/ |archive-date=22 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the pure ethanol fiasco, consumer confidence in ethanol-powered vehicles was restored, allowing a rapid adoption of the flex technology. This was facilitated by the fuel distribution infrastructure already in place throughout Brazil, with more than 30 thousand fueling stations, a heritage of the ''Pr\u00f3-\u00c1lcool'' program<ref name=\"BRgas08\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gazeta.com.br/GZM_News.aspx?Parms=2108086,604,1 |title=Margem estreita n\u00e3o intimida pequenas |publisher=Gazeta Mercantil |author=Roberta Scrivano |date=7 October 2008 |accessdate=26 November 2008 |language=Portuguese }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOwing to the success and rapid consumer acceptance of the flex-fuel versions, by 2005 VW had sold 293,523 flex-fuel cars and light-duty trucks, and only 53,074 gasoline-only automobiles,<ref name=\"ANFAVEA05\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anfavea.com.br/tabelas2005/autoveiculos/tabela08_vendas.pdf|title=Tabela 08 \u2013 Vendas Atacado Mercado Interno por Tipo e Empresa \u2013 Combust\u00edvel Flex Fuel \u2013 2005|publisher=ANFAVEA \u2013 Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional dos Fabricantes de Ve\u00edculos Automotores (Brazil)|accessdate=16 April 2009|language=Portuguese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120082957/http://www.anfavea.com.br/tabelas2005/autoveiculos/tabela08_vendas.pdf|archive-date=20 November 2008|url-status=live}}  ''See Table 08 for flex-fuel sales and Table 07 for gasoline sales''.</ref> jumping to 525,838 flex-fuel vehicles and only 13,572 gasoline-only cars and 248 gasoline-only light trucks in 2007,<ref name=\"ANFAVEA07\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anfavea.com.br/tabelas2007/autoveiculos/tabela08_vendas.pdf|title=Tabela 08 \u2013 Vendas Atacado Mercado Interno por Tipo e Empresa \u2013 Combust\u00edvel Flex Fuel \u2013 2007|publisher=ANFAVEA \u2013 Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional dos Fabricantes de Ve\u00edculos Automotores (Brazil)|accessdate=16 April 2009|language=Portuguese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120041043/http://www.anfavea.com.br/tabelas2007/autoveiculos/tabela08_vendas.pdf|archive-date=20 November 2008|url-status=live}}  ''See Table 08 for flex-fuel sales and Table 07 for gasoline sales''.</ref> and reaching new car sales of 564,959 flex-fuel vehicles in 2008, representing 96% of all new cars and light-duty trucks sold in that year.<ref name=\"ANFAVEA08\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anfavea.com.br/tabelas2008/autoveiculos/tabela08_vendas.pdf|title=Tabela 08 \u2013 Vendas Atacado Mercado Interno por Tipo e Empresa \u2013 Combust\u00edvel Flex Fuel \u2013 2008|publisher=ANFAVEA \u2013 Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional dos Fabricantes de Ve\u00edculos Automotores (Brazil)|accessdate=16 April 2009|language=Portuguese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150754/http://www.anfavea.com.br/tabelas2008/autoveiculos/tabela08_vendas.pdf|archive-date=6 July 2011|url-status=live}}  ''See Table 08''.</ref> VW do Brasil stopped manufacturing gasoline-only vehicles models for the local market in 2006,<ref name=\"autonews.com\" /> and all of the remaining gasoline-only Volkswagen models sold in Brazil are imported. The flex-fuel models currently produced for the local market are the Gol, Fox, CrossFox, Parati, Polo Hatch, Polo Sedan, Saveiro, Golf, and Kombi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norpave.com.br/site/index.php?modulo=detalhe_noticia&id=24 |title=VW completa 55 anos como maior montadora do Pa\u00eds |publisher=Norpave VW |date=25 March 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2009 |language=Portuguese}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> By March 2009, Volkswagen do Brasil had attained the milestone mark of two million flex-fuel vehicles produced since 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autobrasil.wordpress.com/2009/03/25/vw-dois-milhoes-de-carros-flex/|title=VW: dois milh\u00f5es de carros flex|publisher=Auto Brasil|date=25 March 2009|accessdate=19 April 2009|language=Portuguese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090329062920/http://autobrasil.wordpress.com/2009/03/25/vw-dois-milhoes-de-carros-flex/|archive-date=29 March 2009|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.noticiasautomotivas.com.br/volkswagen-atinge-2-milhoes-de-carros-flex-produzidos-no-brasil/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120906165905/http://www.noticiasautomotivas.com.br/volkswagen-atinge-2-milhoes-de-carros-flex-produzidos-no-brasil/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 September 2012 |title=Volkswagen atinge 2 milh\u00f5es de carros Flex produzidos no Brasil |publisher=Noticias Automotivas |date=24 March 2009 |accessdate=18 April 2009 |language=Portuguese }}</ref>\n\n===Hybrid vehicles===\n[[File:VW Jetta Hybrid WAS 2012 0710.JPG|thumb|left|The Volkswagen Jetta Hybrid gets 48 mpg highway.]]\n\nVolkswagen and [[Sanyo]] have teamed up to develop a battery system for [[hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid cars]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theautochannel.com/news/2006/02/03/209275.html |title=Volkswagen and Sanyo Team Up To Develop Hybrid Battery Systems |publisher=Theautochannel.com |accessdate=27 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100912073859/http://www.theautochannel.com/news/2006/02/03/209275.html |archive-date=12 September 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Volkswagen head [[Martin Winterkorn]] has confirmed the company plans to build compact hybrid electric vehicles. He has stated \"There will definitely be compact hybrid models, such as [[Volkswagen Polo|Polo]] and [[Volkswagen Golf|Golf]], and without any great delay\", with gasoline and [[diesel engine|diesel]] power. For example, Golf is the ideal model to go hybrid as the Golf 1.4 TSI was recently awarded the \"Auto Environment Certificate\" by the Oko-Trend Institute for Environmental Research, and was considered as one of the most environmentally friendly vehicles of 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.green-hybrid-cars.com/volkswagen-hybrid.html |title=\"Volkswagen Hybrid: Runaway Winner\". Eco-Friendly Hybrid Cars, 2 May 2008 |publisher=Green-hybrid-cars.com |accessdate=27 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306063534/http://green-hybrid-cars.com/volkswagen-hybrid.html |archive-date=6 March 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Also underway at Volkswagen's [[Braunschweig]] [[Research and development|R&D]] facilities in Northern Germany is a hybrid version of the next-generation [[Volkswagen Touareg|Touareg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=119559 |title=Compact Hybrid Coming From Volkswagen |publisher=Edmunds.com |date=22 January 2009 |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217073817/http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId%3D119559 |archivedate=17 February 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n\nVW intends all future models to have the hybrid option.  \"Future VW models will fundamentally also be constructed with hybrid concepts,\" VW head of development Ulrich Hackenberg told ''Automobilwoche'' in an interview. Hackenberg mentioned that the car based on the [[Volkswagen up!|Up!]] concept seen at [[Frankfurt Motor Show]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=122568 |title=2007 Frankfurt Auto Show: Volkswagen Up! |publisher=Edmunds.com |date=11 September 2007 |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301021345/http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId%3D122568 |archivedate=1 March 2009 |df= }}</ref> as well as all future models, could be offered with either full or partial hybrid options. The rear-engine up! will go into production in 2011. Nothing has been said about [[plug-in hybrid]] options.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.egmcartech.com/2007/09/24/report-all-volkswagen-models-to-have-hybrid-option/ |title=Report: All Volkswagen models to have hybrid option |publisher=eGMCarTech |date=24 September 2007 |accessdate=27 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429001822/http://www.egmcartech.com/2007/09/24/report-all-volkswagen-models-to-have-hybrid-option/ |archive-date=29 April 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVolkswagen announced at the [[Geneva Motor Show#010|2010 Geneva Motor Show]] the launch of the 2012 [[Volkswagen Touareg#Touareg V6 TSI Hybrid (2009)|Touareg Hybrid]], scheduled for 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/03/05/geneva-auto-show-2011-vw-touareg-and-2012-touareg-hybrid/?scp=1&sq=2011%20Volkswagen%20Touareg%20Hybrid&st=cse|title=Geneva Auto Show: 2011 VW Touareg and 2012 Touareg Hybrid|author=Nick Kurczewski|work=The New York Times|date=5 March 2010|accessdate=26 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720075803/http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/03/05/geneva-auto-show-2011-vw-touareg-and-2012-touareg-hybrid/?scp=1&sq=2011%20Volkswagen%20Touareg%20Hybrid&st=cse|archive-date=20 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/suvs/1003_2011_volkswagen_touareg_hybrid_drive/index.html|title=First Drive: 2011 Volkswagen Touareg|author=Scott Evans|magazine=[[Motor Trend]]|date=March 2010|accessdate=26 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322191600/http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/suvs/1003_2011_volkswagen_touareg_hybrid_drive/index.html|archive-date=22 March 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> VW also announced plans to introduce [[diesel fuel|diesel]]-electric hybrid versions of its most popular models in 2012, beginning with the new [[Volkswagen Jetta|Jetta]], followed by the [[Volkswagen Golf|Golf Hybrid]] in 2013 together with hybrid versions of the [[Volkswagen Polo|Passat]].<ref name=Parkers>{{cite web|url=http://www.parkers.co.uk/News/News/VW-hybridelectric-cars/ |title=VW to launch hybrid Jetta in 2012 |publisher=Parker's |accessdate=26 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130114061853/http://www.parkers.co.uk/News/News/VW-hybridelectric-cars/ |archivedate=14 January 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref name=AECs>{{cite web|url=http://www.allcarselectric.com/blog/1043442_vw-to-focus-on-several-electric-and-hybrid-vehicle-launches-including-golf-jetta-passat-and-more |title=VW To Focus on Several Electric and Hybrid Vehicle Launches Including Golf, Jetta, Passat and More |author=Motor Authority|publisher=All Cars Electric|date=17 March 2010|accessdate=26 March 2010}}</ref> In 2012, the Volkswagen Jetta Hybrid set the world record to become the fastest hybrid car at 187&nbsp;mph.\n\n===Plug-in electric vehicles===\n\nIn November 2009, Volkswagen announced it has hired Karl-Thomas Neumann as its group chief officer for [[electric traction]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rumors.automobilemag.com/6605889/news/volkswagen-hires-new-electric-vehicle-chief/index.html |title=Volkswagen Hires New Electric Vehicle Chief \u2013 Automotive News & Car Rumors at Automobile Magazine |publisher=Rumors.automobilemag.com |date=12 November 2009 |accessdate=22 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114153307/http://rumors.automobilemag.com/6605889/news/volkswagen-hires-new-electric-vehicle-chief/index.html |archive-date=14 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> VW's Chief of research, J\u00fcrgen Leohold, said in 2010 the company has concluded [[fuel-cell vehicle|hydrogen fuel-cell cars]] are not a viable option.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.calcars.org/calcars-news/876.html |title=Audi's PHEV Concept; Volkswagen Research Chief Criticizes Fuel Cells |publisher=Calcars.org |accessdate=27 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919130451/http://calcars.org/calcars-news/876.html |archive-date=19 September 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle/Volkswagen-Concepts/229005/ |title=Fuel cell cars won't save the world |work=Autocar |date=6 November 2007 |accessdate=27 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206050703/http://www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle/Volkswagen-Concepts/229005/ |archive-date=6 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Black VW Golf GTE charging fl, Amsterdam (20150224 102438).jpg|thumb|[[Volkswagen Golf GTE]] [[plug-in hybrid]] charging.]]\n\n{{As of|2016|05}}, the [[Volkswagen Group]] offers for retails customers nine [[plug-in electric car]]s, of which, three are [[all-electric car]]s: the [[Volkswagen e-Up!]], [[Volkswagen e-Golf|e-Golf]] and [[Audi R8 e-tron]], and six are [[plug-in hybrid]]s: the [[Volkswagen Golf GTE]], [[Volkswagen Passat GTE|Passat GTE]], [[Audi A3 Sportback e-tron]], [[Audi Q7 e-tron|Q7 e-tron quattro]], [[Porsche Panamera S E-Hybrid]] and [[Porsche Cayenne S E-Hybrid|Cayenne S E-Hybrid]].<ref name=VWPEVs>{{cite news | url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20160529/OEM05/305309985/vw-goal:-1-million-electrified-vehicles-by-2025 | title=VW goal: 1 million electrified vehicles by 2025 | first=Christiaan | last= Hetzner | work=[[Automotive News]] | date=29 May 2016 | accessdate=29 May 2016}}</ref> Also two limited production plug-in hybrids were manufactured beginning in 2013, the [[Volkswagen XL1]] (250 units) and the [[Porsche 918 Spyder]] (918 units).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.automobilwoche.de/article/20131009/NACHRICHTEN/131009943/vergabe-der-kleinstserie-vw-lenkt-xl-1-fans-auf-zielgerade|title=Vergabe der Kleinstserie: VW lenkt XL-1-Fans auf Zielgerade|language=German|trans-title=Allocation of micro series: VW XL1 draws fans to finish line|author=Henning Kroghhkrogh|work=Automobilwoche|date=9 October 2013|accessdate=26 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029185025/http://www.automobilwoche.de/article/20131009/NACHRICHTEN/131009943/vergabe-der-kleinstserie-vw-lenkt-xl-1-fans-auf-zielgerade|archive-date=29 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2012/10/01/2014-porsche-918-spyder-deep-dive-review/ |title=2014 Porsche 918 Spyder |author=Michael Harley |publisher=[[Autoblog.com]] |date=1 October 2012 |accessdate=14 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005115349/http://www.autoblog.com/2012/10/01/2014-porsche-918-spyder-deep-dive-review/ |archive-date=5 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Total cumulative sales of all Volkswagen brand [[electric vehicle|electrified cars]] since the start of their respective production is expected to reach about 103,000 by the end of 2016.<ref name=VWPEVs/>\n\nIn order to comply with increasingly strict carbon dioxide emission limits in major markets, the VW Group expects to sell about one million all-electric and plug-in hybrid vehicles a year worldwide by 2025. The Group plans to expand its plug-in range with 20 new pure electric and plug-in hybrid cars, including two cars to compete with [[Tesla Motors]], the [[Porsche Mission E]] all-electric car and the [[Audi e-tron (2018)|Audi e-tron]] quattro, which is expected to become the brand's first mass-production electric vehicle. According to Thomas Ulbrich, VW brand production chief, the carmaker has the capacity to build as many as 75,000 battery-electric and plug-in hybrids a year if demand rises. Volkswagen announced in October 2015 that \"it will develop a modular architecture for battery-electric cars, called the [[Volkswagen Group MEB platform|MEB]]. The standardized system will be designed for all body structures and vehicle types and will allow the company to build emotionally appealing EVs with a range of up to {{convert|310|mi|abbr=on}}.\"<ref name=VWPEVs/> In June 2016, VW launched a program to develop 30 all-electric cars in 10 years, and sell 2\u20133&nbsp;million electric cars per year by 2025.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkswagenag.com/content/vwcorp/info_center/en/news/2016/06/2025.html |title=News|accessdate=20 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160621062535/http://www.volkswagenag.com/content/vwcorp/info_center/en/news/2016/06/2025.html |archivedate=21 June 2016  }}</ref> Due to lower manpower requirements for electric motors than for piston engines, VW expects a gradual workforce reduction as numbers of electric cars increase.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-volkswagen-jobs-idUSKCN12S1QP|title=VW HR chief says expects five-digit number of job cuts: FAZ|date=29 October 2016|agency=Reuters|accessdate=1 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161101191653/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-volkswagen-jobs-idUSKCN12S1QP|archive-date=1 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/neue-mobilitaet/vw-personalchef-elektromobilitaet-wird-zehntausende-jobs-kosten-14502483.html|title=VW-Personalchef: Elektromobilit\u00e4t wird Zehntausende Jobs kosten|date=28 October 2016|work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|accessdate=1 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031214937/http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/neue-mobilitaet/vw-personalchef-elektromobilitaet-wird-zehntausende-jobs-kosten-14502483.html|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> VW considers battery factory ownership as too expensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/neue-mobilitaet/osterloh-besteht-auf-bau-einer-batteriefabrik-14486729.html|title=Osterloh besteht auf Bau einer Batteriefabrik|date=18 October 2016|work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|accessdate=1 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103235035/http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/neue-mobilitaet/osterloh-besteht-auf-bau-einer-batteriefabrik-14486729.html|archive-date=3 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n{{See also|List of companies involved in the Holocaust}}\n\n===Environmental record===\n[[File:VW XL 1 vr.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Volkswagen XL1]], with potential mileage as high as 261 mpg, is the most fuel-efficient car in the world]]\n\nIn 1974 Volkswagen paid a $120,000 fine to settle a complaint filed by the Environmental Protection Agency over the use of so-called \"defeat devices\" that disabled certain pollution-control systems. The complaint said the use of the devices violated the U.S. Clean Air Act.<ref>{{cite web|title=VW had previous run-in over 'defeat devices'|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/09/23/vw-had-previous-run-in-over-defeat-devices.html|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=18 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013174105/http://www.cnbc.com/2015/09/23/vw-had-previous-run-in-over-defeat-devices.html|archive-date=13 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Volkswagen first implemented its seven environmental goals in Technical Development with themes involving climate protection, resource conservation, and healthcare, through objectives such as reducing greenhouse emissions and fuel consumption, enabling alternative fuels, and avoiding hazardous materials.<ref name=Volkswagen_Environment>{{cite web|url=http://www.volkswagen.com/vwcms/master_public/virtualmaster/en2/unternehmen/mobility_and_sustainability0/management___daten/management_und_verantwortung/Umweltziele.html |title=Volkswagen Environmental |author=Volkswagen |publisher=Volkswagen |date=12 December 2010 |accessdate=12 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226110727/http://www.volkswagen.com/vwcms/master_public/virtualmaster/en2/unternehmen/mobility_and_sustainability0/management___daten/management_und_verantwortung/Umweltziele.html |archivedate=26 February 2011 }}</ref> The goals have been revised in 2002 and 2007. Volkswagen was the first car manufacturer to apply [[ISO 14000]], during its drafting stage and was re-certified under the standards in September 2005.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nIn 2011, [[Greenpeace]] began criticising Volkswagen's opposition to legislation requiring tighter controls on CO2 emissions and energy efficiency, and launched an advertising campaign parodying VW's series of ''[[Star Wars]]''-based commercials.<ref name=Volkswagen_Environment /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://vwdarkside.com |title=Volkswagen. The Dark Side. |publisher=Greenpeace |accessdate=31 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804163538/http://www.vwdarkside.com/ |archive-date=4 August 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the Volkswagen XL1 became the most fuel-efficient production car in the world, with a claimed combined fuel consumption of 261 mpg (0.90-liter/100&nbsp;km). [[Energy-efficient driving|Driving style]] has huge impact on this result \u2013 \"normal\" driving produces mileage in the 120 mpg range (1.96-liter/100&nbsp;km).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobilemag.com/reviews/driven/1307_2014_volkswagen_xl1/|title=2014 Volkswagen XL1 First Drive|date=20 May 2013|work=Automobile|accessdate=22 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923190829/http://www.automobilemag.com/reviews/driven/1307_2014_volkswagen_xl1/|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nModel year 2017 VW vehicles sold in the US average 26.5 mpg<sub>US</sub>, about 6% better than the average for all manufacturers. For comparison among major automakers, Honda lead at 29.4 mpg<sub>US</sub> while FCA, the owner of Jeep, Ram, Chrysler, Fiat, and Dodge brands, lagged at 21.2 mpg<sub>US</sub>.<ref>{{cite web |title=Highlights of the Automotive Trends Report |url=https://www.epa.gov/automotive-trends/highlights-automotive-trends-report |website=US EPA |publisher=Office of Air and Radiation |accessdate=July 25, 2019 |language=en |date=March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801095945/https://www.epa.gov/automotive-trends/highlights-automotive-trends-report |archive-date=1 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====US diesel emission fraud====\n{{main|Volkswagen emissions scandal}}\n[[File:'09 Volkswagen Jetta Diesel Sedan (MIAS).JPG|thumb|The 2009 Volkswagen Jetta Diesel Sedan was awarded [[Green Car of the Year]]. The award was rescinded in early October 2015.]]\nOn 18 September 2015, the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) said beginning in 2008 the automaker improperly installed [[engine control unit]] (ECU) software determined to be a \"defeat device\", in violation of the [[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act]], to circumvent environmental regulations of [[NOx|NO<sub>''x''</sub>]] emissions by [[diesel engine]] 2009\u20132015 model year Volkswagen and Audi cars. The software detects when the cars were being subject to emissions testing, and then fully enabled ECU emission controls to successfully pass.<ref>{{cite news|title=Auto expert: 'A conscious breach of US law'|url=http://www.dw.com/en/auto-expert-a-conscious-breach-of-us-law/a-18728394|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=21 September 2015|access-date=21 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923004527/http://www.dw.com/en/auto-expert-a-conscious-breach-of-us-law/a-18728394|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2015/09/20150918-epaarb.html|title=Green Car Congress: EPA and California ARB charge Volkswagen with using software defeat device to circumvent NOx testing in 4-cylinder 2.0L dieselss|website=Greencarcongress.com|accessdate=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724190717/http://www.greencarcongress.com/2015/09/20150918-epaarb.html|archive-date=24 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> However, during normal driving conditions, emission control software was shut off in order to attain greater fuel economy and additional power, resulting in as much as 40 times more pollution than allowed by law.<ref>Krall JR, Peng RD. The Volkswagen scandal: Deception, driving and deaths. Significance. 2015;12(6):12-5.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = VW, Audi Cited by EPA for Cheating on Diesel Emissions Tests|url = http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/cars/vw--audi-cited-by-epa-for-cheating-on-diesel-emissions-tests|accessdate = 26 September 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150926214553/http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/cars/vw--audi-cited-by-epa-for-cheating-on-diesel-emissions-tests|archive-date = 26 September 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> ''[[Consumer Reports]]'' tested a 2011 Jetta SportWagen TDI and found in emissions mode its 0\u201360&nbsp;mph time increased by 0.6 seconds and its highway fuel economy dropped from 50 mpg to 46 mpg.<ref name=Fisher2015>{{Citation |url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/cars/testing-volkswagen-diesel-fuel-economy-and-performance-in-cheat-mode |title=Consumer Reports Tests VW Diesel Fuel Economy, Performance in 'Cheat' Mode; Tests reveal different results when the 'cheat' settings are used in the real world |first=Jake |last=Fisher |date=9 October 2015 |magazine=[[Consumer Reports]] |access-date=24 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414202408/https://www.consumerreports.org/cro/cars/testing-volkswagen-diesel-fuel-economy-and-performance-in-cheat-mode |archive-date=14 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Volkswagen admitted to using the defeat device, and has been ordered to recall approximately 482,000 cars with four-cylinder 2.0-liter [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]] engines.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ewing|first1=Jack|title=Volkswagen Says 11 Million Cars Worldwide Are Affected in Diesel Deception|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/23/business/international/volkswagen-diesel-car-scandal.html|work=The New York Times|date=22 September 2015|access-date=20 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304002510/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/23/business/international/volkswagen-diesel-car-scandal.html|archive-date=4 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> United States federal penalties may include fines ranging up to US$18{{nbsp}}billion, and possibly criminal charges.<ref name=\"NYT EPA\">{{Cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/19/business/volkswagen-is-ordered-to-recall-nearly-500000-vehicles-over-emissions-software.html| title=VW Is Said to Cheat on Diesel Emissions; U.S. Orders Big Recall| first1=Coral| last1=Davenport| first2=Jack| last2=Ewing| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| date=18 September 2015| accessdate=18 September 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150918180427/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/19/business/volkswagen-is-ordered-to-recall-nearly-500000-vehicles-over-emissions-software.html| archive-date=18 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 June 2016, Volkswagen agreed to pay a settlement of $15.3&nbsp;billion, the largest auto-related consumer class-action lawsuit in the United States history.<ref>{{cite web |author=Michael Lewis |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/06/28/volkswagen-agrees-to-landmark-147-billion-emissions-settlement-in-us.html |title=Volkswagen agrees to landmark $15.3-billion emissions settlement in U.S. |website=Toronto Star |date=28 June 2016 |accessdate=24 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113222545/https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/06/28/volkswagen-agrees-to-landmark-147-billion-emissions-settlement-in-us.html |archive-date=13 November 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, the [[EPA]] was first alerted to the issue by the [[International Council on Clean Transportation]] (ICCT), reporting results<ref name=\"CAFEE\">{{Cite report| url=http://www.theicct.org/sites/default/files/publications/WVU_LDDV_in-use_ICCT_Report_Final_may2014.pdf| title=In-Use Emissions Testing of Light-Duty Diesel Vehicles in the United States| first1=Gregory J.| last1=Thompson| first2=Daniel K.| last2=Carder| first3=Marc C.| last3=Besch| first4=Arvind| last4=Thiruvengadam| first5=Hemanth K.| last5=Kappanna| publisher=Center for Alternative Fuels, Engines and Emissions (CAFEE), [[University of West Virginia]]| date=18 September 2015| accessdate=18 September 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922201130/http://www.theicct.org/sites/default/files/publications/WVU_LDDV_in-use_ICCT_Report_Final_may2014.pdf| archivedate=22 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> of research commissioned for them by [[West Virginia University]]'s Center for Alternative Fuels, Engines and Emissions (CAFEE).<ref name=\"CandD\">{{Cite news| url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/volkswagen-allegedly-openly-violated-epa-diesel-laws-could-face-billions-in-fines/| title=Volkswagen Allegedly Openly Violated EPA Diesel Laws, Could Face Billions in Fines| first1=Clifford| last1=Atiyeh| magazine=Car and Driver| date=18 September 2015| accessdate=18 September 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920133141/http://blog.caranddriver.com/volkswagen-allegedly-openly-violated-epa-diesel-laws-could-face-billions-in-fines/| archive-date=20 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cafee.wvu.edu/|title=WVU Center for Alternative Fuels Engines and Emissions|website=Cafee.wvu.edu|accessdate=22 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923055936/http://cafee.wvu.edu/|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> After 15 months of denying the emissions control systems were deliberately gamed and instead claiming discrepancies due to \"technical\" reasons, on 21 August Volkswagen acknowledged to the EPA and [[California Air Resources Board]] (CARB) their emission controls systems were rigged. This was followed by a formal announcement of admission to regulators on 3 September which took place immediately after the EPA threatened to withhold approval for their 2016 cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20150924/OEM/150929873/vw-after-a-year-of-stonewalling-stunned-u-s-regulators-with|title=VW, after a year of stonewalling, stunned U.S. regulators with confession|website=Autonews.com|accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref> Volkswagen's initial public response came on 20 September, when a spokesman said they would stop all US sales of the diesel models affected. Chairman Martin Winterkorn issued an apology and said Volkswagen would cooperate with investigators.<ref name=Ewing2015a>{{Citation |title= Volkswagen to Stop Sales of Diesel Cars Involved in Recall |first1= Jack |last1= Ewing |first2= Coral |last2= Davenport |date= 20 September 2015 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/21/business/international/volkswagen-chief-apologizes-for-breach-of-trust-after-recall.html |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |access-date= 20 February 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170119023329/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/21/business/international/volkswagen-chief-apologizes-for-breach-of-trust-after-recall.html |archive-date= 19 January 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> Since emission standards in Canada are close to those in the US, Volkswagen Canada also halted sales of the affected diesel models.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/volkswagen-emissions-rigging-1.3236548|title=Volkswagen Canada halts some sales as emissions rigging scandal deepens|date=22 September 2015|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=22 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921180145/http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/volkswagen-emissions-rigging-1.3236548|archive-date=21 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> on 22 September 2015, Volkswagen spokesman admitted that the defeat device is installed in ~11&nbsp;million vehicles with Type [[EA 189]] diesel engines worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/volkswagen-emissions-scandal-relates-to-11-million-cars-1442916906 |title=Volkswagen Emissions Scandal Relates to 11 Million Cars |author1=William Boston |author2=Sarah Sloat |lastauthoramp=yes |date=22 September 2015 |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=12 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302023415/https://www.wsj.com/articles/volkswagen-emissions-scandal-relates-to-11-million-cars-1442916906 |archive-date=2 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn the first business day after the news, Volkswagen's stock price declined 20% and declined another 17% the following day, the same day a social media advertisement with ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' about \"how diesel was re-engineered\" was removed as well as a series of YouTube ads titled \"Diesel Old Wives\u2019 Tales\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adage.com/article/cmo-strategy/wired-s-native-ad-volkswagen-diesel-tech-missing/300496/|title=Wired's Native Ad for Volkswagen Diesel Tech Goes Missing|website=Advertising Age|accessdate=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629115408/http://adage.com/article/cmo-strategy/wired-s-native-ad-volkswagen-diesel-tech-missing/300496/|archive-date=29 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Ewing2015b>{{Citation |title= Volkswagen Denied Deception to E.P.A. for Nearly a Year |first1= Jack |last1= Ewing |date= 21 September 2015 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/22/business/international/volkswagen-shares-recall.html |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |access-date= 20 February 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170131110445/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/22/business/international/volkswagen-shares-recall.html |archive-date= 31 January 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Why Did Volkswagen Delete All of Its Diesel Ads From YouTube?|url = http://jalopnik.com/why-did-volkswagen-delete-all-of-its-diesel-ads-from-yo-1731691453|accessdate = 26 September 2015|first = Michael|last = Ballaban|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150926172710/http://jalopnik.com/why-did-volkswagen-delete-all-of-its-diesel-ads-from-yo-1731691453|archive-date = 26 September 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> On Wednesday, 23 September, Volkswagen chief executive officer [[Martin Winterkorn]] resigned.<ref name=VWrefuses>{{Citation |title= Volkswagen chief executive Martin Winterkorn resigns |date= 23 September 2015 |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34340997 |publisher= [[BBC UK]] |access-date= 21 July 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181107193944/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34340997 |archive-date= 7 November 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> Volkswagen hired [[Kirkland & Ellis]] law firm for defense, the same firm that defended [[BP]] during the [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20150923/OEM01/150929934 |title=Volkswagen hires law firm that defended BP after oil spill|work=Automotive News}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Martin Winterkorn 2015-03-13 001.jpg|thumb|Former Volkswagen AG CEO [[Martin Winterkorn]] in March 2015]]\nOn 2 November 2016, the EPA issued a second notice of violation (NOV) pertaining to certain diesel 3.0-liter [[V6]] equipped Audis, [[Volkswagen Touareg]]s and [[Porsche Cayenne]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yosemite.epa.gov/opa/admpress.nsf/0/4A45A5661216E66C85257EF10061867B |title=Press |accessdate=3 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105103847/http://yosemite.epa.gov/opa/admpress.nsf/0/4A45A5661216E66C85257EF10061867B |archivedate=5 November 2015  }}</ref> The EPA found beginning with the 2009 model year all vehicles powered by the V6 were non-compliant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20151120/OEM11/151129977/vws-3-0-liter-diesels-under-wider-scrutiny-by-epa-carb|title=VW's 3.0-liter diesels under wider scrutiny by EPA, CARB|website=Autonews.com|accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref> During testing the EPA, CARB and Transport Canada discovered software that activates pollution reduction systems when the automobiles are being driven under federal test conditions, otherwise during real world driving these devices are inactive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20151103/COPY01/311039953/vw-prepares-to-fight-latest-diesel-cheating-allegations|title=VW prepares to fight latest diesel cheating allegations|website=Autonews.com|accessdate=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620120553/http://www.autonews.com/article/20151103/COPY01/311039953/vw-prepares-to-fight-latest-diesel-cheating-allegations|archive-date=20 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20151102/OEM01/151109977/vw-porsche-audi-3-0-liter-diesels-also-have-defeat-devices-epa-says|title=VW, Porsche, Audi 3.0-liter diesels also have 'defeat devices,' EPA sayss|website=Autonews.com|accessdate=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215121213/https://www.autonews.com/article/20151102/OEM01/151109977/vw-porsche-audi-3-0-liter-diesels-also-have-defeat-devices-epa-says|archive-date=15 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Volkswagen disputed the EPA's findings stating their software was legally permitted,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/epa-notifies-volkswagen-of-added-emissions-violations-1446491504|title=EPA, Volkswagen Spar Over New Emissions Claims|first1=Mike|last1=Spector|first2=William|last2=Boston|date=4 November 2015|website=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=4 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821123034/https://www.wsj.com/articles/epa-notifies-volkswagen-of-added-emissions-violations-1446491504|archive-date=21 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> however shortly after Volkswagen issued a stop-sale for the EPA's disputed vehicles and additional models the EPA did not question.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1100782_audi-porsche-vw-diesel-stop-sale-orders-more-cars-than-epa-named|title=Audi, Porsche, VW Diesel Stop-Sale Orders: More Cars Than EPA Named|website=Greencarreports.com|accessdate=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701195424/http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1100782_audi-porsche-vw-diesel-stop-sale-orders-more-cars-than-epa-named|archive-date=1 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the US [[Federal Trade Commission]] sued Volkswagen for false advertising, because Volkswagen's \"clean diesel\" vehicles were less environmentally friendly than advertised.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20160329/RETAIL03/160329857/vws-u-s-arm-sued-by-ftc-over-clean-diesel-ads|title=VW's U.S. arm sued by FTC over 'clean diesel' ads|website=Autonews.com|accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Volkswagen and its labour unions agreed to reduce the workforce by 30,000 people until 2021 as a result of the costs from the violations. However, 9,000 new jobs would come by producing more electric cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/11/18/volkswagen-vw-job-cuts/|title=Volkswagen Is Said to Be Cutting 30,000 Jobs|date=18 November 2016|work=Fortune|accessdate=18 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119115753/http://fortune.com/2016/11/18/volkswagen-vw-job-cuts/|archive-date=19 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Volkswagen also announced plans to become the world leader in electric cars, producing 1 million VW-EVs by 2025 and 3&nbsp;million by the group,<ref>DAVID McHUGH. \"[https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2016-11-22/volkswagen-aims-to-go-electric-raise-lagging-profits VW Betting on New Technology] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123054906/http://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2016-11-22/volkswagen-aims-to-go-electric-raise-lagging-profits |date=23 November 2016 }}\" [[Associated Press]], 22 November 2016.</ref> and a VW manager stated that its diesel cars would not become available in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://global.handelsblatt.com/breaking/vw-to-withdraw-from-u-s-diesel-market|title=VW to Withdraw from U.S. Diesel Market|work=[[Handelsblatt]] Global Edition|accessdate=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123053247/https://global.handelsblatt.com/breaking/vw-to-withdraw-from-u-s-diesel-market|archive-date=23 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 January 2017, Volkswagen agreed to plead guilty to the emissions-cheating scandal and to pay $4.3&nbsp;billion in penalties. Six Volkswagen executives were charged.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ewing|first1=Hiroko Tabuchi, Jack|last2=Apuzzo|first2=Matt|title=Six Volkswagen Executives Charged in Emissions Scandal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/11/business/volkswagen-diesel-vw-settlement-charges-criminal.html|accessdate=11 January 2017|work=The New York Times|date=11 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112014855/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/11/business/volkswagen-diesel-vw-settlement-charges-criminal.html|archive-date=12 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Shepardson|first1=David|title=U.S. indicts six as Volkswagen agrees to $4.3&nbsp;billion diesel settlement|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-volkswagen-emissions-idUKKBN14V2E0|accessdate=11 January 2017|agency=Reuters UK|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111202351/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-volkswagen-emissions-idUKKBN14V2E0|archive-date=11 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, one of the indicted executives was ordered to be held without bail pending trial as it was feared that he would flee to Germany and extradition would be impossible.<ref>{{cite news|title=Judge denies bail for indicted Volkswagen executive|url=http://hosted2.ap.org/APDEFAULT/386c25518f464186bf7a2ac026580ce7/Article_2017-01-12-US--Volkswagen-Emissions%20Scandal-Executive/id-3fe7c76adf684f558efec41a3eac788d|accessdate=12 January 2017|agency=Associated Press|date=12 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113170252/http://hosted2.ap.org/APDEFAULT/386c25518f464186bf7a2ac026580ce7/Article_2017-01-12-US--Volkswagen-Emissions%20Scandal-Executive/id-3fe7c76adf684f558efec41a3eac788d|archive-date=13 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. judge orders Volkswagen executive detained|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-volkswagen-emissions-idUSKBN14W2YZ|accessdate=12 January 2017|agency=Reuters|date=12 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113074029/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-volkswagen-emissions-idUSKBN14W2YZ|archive-date=13 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Senior VW management staff were warned not to travel to the US by lawyers working for the company.<ref>{{cite news|title=Senior VW managers warned not to travel to U.S.: sources|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-volkswagen-emissions-extradition-idUSKBN14X175|accessdate=13 January 2017|agency=Reuters|date=13 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113120604/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-volkswagen-emissions-extradition-idUSKBN14X175|archive-date=13 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 January 2017, a US judge approved a $1.2&nbsp;billion settlement in which 650 American dealers, \"who, like consumers, were blindsided by the brazen fraud that VW perpetrated,\" would receive an average of $1.85&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. judge approves Volkswagen dealers $1.2&nbsp;billion settlement|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-volkswagen-emissions-idUSKBN1572SC|accessdate=24 January 2017|agency=Reuters|date=24 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123235506/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-volkswagen-emissions-idUSKBN1572SC|archive-date=23 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Canadian emissions charges===\nOn December 9, 2019, Environment and Climate Change Canada charged Volkswagen AG with importing nearly 128,000 cars into Canada that did not meet its emissions standards, but reached a plea deal with the agency in a case involving 60 charges stemming from devices installed to defeat emissions testing.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Financial Post |date=December 10, 2019 |author=Emily Jackson |title=Volkswagen reaches plea deal with Ottawa |page=FP3}}</ref>\n\n===Collaboration with dictatorship ===\nIn 2015, activists and former VW employees in [[Brazil]] spoke out in public accusing the company of being silent about the persecution of its workers, which was during [[Brazilian military government|Brazil's military dictatorship]] from 1964-1985.<ref>[http://www.dw.com/en/vw-worked-hand-in-hand-with-brazils-military-dictatorship/a-39814070 VW worked hand in hand with Brazil's military dictatorship] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724135938/http://www.dw.com/en/vw-worked-hand-in-hand-with-brazils-military-dictatorship/a-39814070 |date=24 July 2017 }}. Deutsche Welle. 24 July 2017</ref> VW's security personnel informed Brazil's political police on eventual oppositional activities. In 1976, mass arrests occurred and some VW employees were tortured.<ref>Agence France Presse [http://fp.brecorder.com/2017/07/20170725201358/ Volkswagen aided Brazil dictatorship\u2019s repression: historian] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831050048/http://fp.brecorder.com/2017/07/20170725201358/ |date=31 August 2017 }} Business Recorder REPORT, 25 July 2017</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n[[File:Volkswagen Polo 2011 (7708695660).jpg|thumb|right|The [[Volkswagen Polo]] in Christchurch, New Zealand. The Volkswagen Polo won the 2010 World Car of the Year]]\n[[File:VW take up! 1.0 \u2013 Frontansicht, 25. Februar 2012, D\u00fcsseldorf.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Volkswagen up!]] won the 2012 World Car of the Year]]\n\nVolkswagen was named the fourth most influential car of the 20th century in the 1999 [[Car of the Century]] competition, for its [[Volkswagen Beetle|Volkswagen Type 1 'Beetle\" model]]. It trailed only the [[Ford Model T]], BMC [[Mini]], and [[Citro\u00ebn DS]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/12/24/automobiles/this-just-in-model-t-gets-award.html|title=This Just In: Model T Gets Award|first=James G.|last=Cobb|date=24 December 1999|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=20 February 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69yoBCGUb?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1999/12/24/automobiles/this-just-in-model-t-gets-award.html|archive-date=17 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVolkswagen has produced four winners of the 50-year-old [[European Car of the Year]] award.\n\n{{unbulleted list|1992 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Golf]]|2010 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Polo]]|2013 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Golf]]|2015 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Passat]]}}\n\nVolkswagen has produced five winners of the United States [[Motor Trend Car of the Year]] award&nbsp;\u2013 the original [[Car of the Year]] designation, which began in 1949.\n\n{{unbulleted list|1985 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen GTI]]|1999 \u2013 [[Volkswagen New Beetle]] (Import COTY subgroup)|2004 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Touareg]] ([[Sport Utility Vehicle]] COTY subgroup)  |2012 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Passat]]|2015 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Golf#Seventh generation (A7, Typ 5G; 2013\u2013present)|Volkswagen Golf line-up]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2014/11/20141113-golf.html|title=Volkswagen Golf family named '2015 Motor Trend Car of the Year'|author=Mike Millikin|publisher=Green Car Congress|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141117120041/http://www.greencarcongress.com/2014/11/20141113-golf.html|archive-date=17 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\nVolkswagen has already produced four winners of the recently developed [[World Car of the Year]] award.\n\n{{unbulleted list|2009 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Golf]]|2010 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Polo]]|2012 \u2013 [[Volkswagen up!]]|2013 \u2013 [[Volkswagen Golf]]}}\n\n==Motorsport==\n{{main|Volkswagen Motorsport}}\n\n===Formula racing===\n\n* In 1963, [[Formula Vee]] circuit racing, with cars built from easily available [[Volkswagen Beetle#Power|Beetle]] parts, started in the United States. It quickly spread to Europe and other parts of the world. It proved very popular as a low-cost route into [[formula racing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.formulaveesa.org.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=51&Itemid=62 |title=South African Formula Vee History |publisher=Formulaveesa.org.za |date=17 May 2009 |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051222041929/http://www.geeky.net/geeky.css |archivedate= 22 December 2005 }}</ref>\n* In 1971, Volkswagen of America started the more powerful [[Formula Super Vee]], which became famous for hothousing new talent.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}} In the 11 years it ran, until 1982, it produced a stable of world-famous [[Formula One]] drivers\u2014names like [[Niki Lauda]], [[Jochen Mass]], [[Nelson Piquet]], [[Jochen Rindt]] and [[Keke Rosberg]]. Volkswagen also notched up several victories, and the championship in [[Formula Three]].\n* In July 2011 Wolfgang D\u00fcrheimer, the director of Bugatti and Bentley, told German magazine ''[[Auto, Motor und Sport]]'' that \"if [the VW group] is at the forefront of the auto industry, I can imagine us competing in Formula 1 in 2018.  We have enough brands to pull it off.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Volkswagen in F1 by 2018? |url=http://europeancarnews.com/2011/07/28/volkswagen-in-f1-by-2018/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608090351/http://europeancarnews.com/2011/07/28/volkswagen-in-f1-by-2018/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 June 2019 |publisher=European Car News |accessdate=28 July 2011 }}</ref> They did not compete in F1 in 2018.\n\n===World Rally Championship===\n* In 1981, now based in [[Hanover]], VW took a new direction into rallying, with the launch of the first-generation Golf, and Sweden's [[Per Eklund]], Frenchman [[Jean-Luc Th\u00e9rier]], and the Finn [[Pentti Airikkala]]. The final chapters in Volkswagen Racing UK's rallying story were the 'one-make' Castrol Polo Challenge, and the Polo GTI 'Super 1600' in 2001.\n* Volkswagen Motorsport won the [[World Rally Championship]] with [[S\u00e9bastien Ogier]] and co-driver [[Julien Ingrassia]] four years in a row from 2013 to 2016 in the [[Volkswagen Polo R WRC]].\n\n===Dakar Rally===\n* In 1980, Volkswagen competed with the Audi-developed [[Volkswagen Iltis|Iltis]], placing 1st, 2nd, 4th and 9th overall.\n* In 2003, the Hanover-based team entered with a 2WD buggy named Tarek, finishing 6th overall and 1st in the 2WD and Diesel class. \n* In 2005, an updated Race-Touareg with slightly more power entered, with driver [[Bruno Saby]] finishing 3rd overall and 1st in the Diesel class. \n* In 2006, the revised Race-Touareg entered, with driver [[Giniel de Villiers]] finishing 2nd overall and 1st in the Diesel class. \n* Volkswagen won the [[2009 Dakar Rally|2009]], [[2010 Dakar Rally|2010]] and [[2011 Dakar Rally]], held in South America.\n\n===Volkswagen motorsport worldwide===\n* Europe: In 1998 the company founded the ADAC Volkswagen Lupo Cup, founded in 1998 (renamed Polo Cup in 2003, and [[Volkswagen Scirocco R-Cup]] from 2010 to 2014), and started the ADAC [[Volkswagen New Beetle|New Beetle]] Cup in 2000. In 2004, [[Volkswagen Commercial Vehicles]] entered the [[European Truck Racing]] series with the Volkswagen Titan truck&nbsp;\u2013 it became a back-to-back champion for the 2004 and 2005 series.\n* United States: In 1976, Volkswagen entered the under-2000-cc [[Trans-Am Series]], with the Scirocco, and they won their class outright.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v243/europlus/77sciroccotransam.jpg |title=Scirocco Trans Am Article/Advert |accessdate=27 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304031436/http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v243/europlus/77sciroccotransam.jpg |archive-date=4 March 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Beginning in 2008 Volkswagen introduced the Jetta TDI Cup. The Jetta TDI Cup is an SCCA sanctioned race series that features 25 drivers between the ages of 16 and 26 driving slightly modified 2009 Jetta TDIs. The series features 10 events at 8 different road courses across North America. There is $50,000 prize money at stake over the course of the series in addition to the $100,000 prize awarded to the champion of the series at the conclusion of the last race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vw.com/vwbuzz/browse/en/us/detail/Twenty_two_drivers_qualify_for_2010_Volkswagen_Jetta_TDI_Cup_final_driver_selection_event/339 |title=Twenty two drivers qualify for 2010 Volkswagen Jetta TDI Cup final driver selection event |website=VW.com |accessdate=22 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826224542/http://www.vw.com/vwbuzz/browse/en/us/detail/Twenty_two_drivers_qualify_for_2010_Volkswagen_Jetta_TDI_Cup_final_driver_selection_event/339 |archivedate=26 August 2010 }}</ref>\n* Argentina: Many Volkswagen models have competed in [[TC 2000]], including the 1980 to 1983 champion [[Hillman Avenger#Argentina|Volkswagen 1500]] and the 1994 champion [[Volkswagen Gol]].\n* In 1999 and 2000, VW won the F2 Australian Rally Championship with the Golf GTI.\n* Finland: In 2002, VW won the [[Finnish Rally Championship]] in a7/(F2), with a Golf Mk4 KitCar, with [[Mikko Hirvonen]]. In 1999 and 2000, VW won the Finnish Rally Championship in a7/(F2) with a Golf Mk3 KitCar. In 2000, 2001 and 2002, VW won the Finnish Racing Championship in Sport 2000 with a Golf Mk4.<ref>[[:de:Deutsche Tourenwagen Challenge|DTC]] {{in lang|de}}</ref>\n* Austria: From 1967 until 1974, the Austrian sole distributor [[Porsche Salzburg]] entered the [[VW Beetle]] (1500, 1302S and 1303S) in Europe-wide rallies. Victories were achieved in 1972 and 1973 in the overall Austrian championship, on Elba, in the Acropolis rally (first in class). Top drivers were [[Tony Fall]] (GB), [[Achim Warmbold]] (D), G\u00fcnter Janger (A), [[Harry K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m]](S).\n\n<div class=\"center\"><gallery>\nFile:VW Typ 60 K 10 - Porsche Typ 64 (Berlin-Rom-Wagen), Bj.1939.jpg|1939 Berlin to Rome. Porsche Type 64 racer based on [[Volkswagen Beetle|Beetle]] platform\nFile:Volkswagen Beetle Fittipaldi-Baldahl 1967.jpg|Twin-engine racing [[Volkswagen Beetle|Beetle]] developed by [[Wilson Fittipaldi J\u00fanior|Wilson]] and [[Emerson Fittipaldi]] brothers\nFile:TC2000 Sportteam Competicion 2006 Volkswagen Bora.jpg|[[Volkswagen Bora|Bora]] in [[TC 2000]], a national championship of Argentina\nFile:Stock Car V8 Brasil Amir Nasr Racing.jpg|[[Volkswagen Bora|Bora]] in [[Stock Car Brasil]]\nFile:VW Race Touareg 2 blue vl EMS.jpg|Edition 2007 Race [[Volkswagen Touareg|Touareg 2]] at Essen Motor Show 2006\nFile:Formula Truck 2006 Interlagos Volkswagen leads.jpg|[[Volkswagen Constellation|Constellation]] in the 2006 Brazilian [[F\u00f3rmula Truck]] Championship\n</gallery></div>\n\n<!--\n\n'''Volkswagen 2016'''\n\nDespite the ongoing emissions scandal, VW's production for the first six months' of 2016 has been confirmed at 5,268,000 cars. Toyota produced 5,033,177 cars, while GM's total figure has yet to be released, but is known to be smaller.[[citation needed|date=June 2017]]\n\nThese figures change slightly when car sales are taken into account: Volkswagen Group sold 5,199,000 cars, while Toyota sold 4,991,741 across its four brands: Toyota, Lexus, Daihatsu, and Hino. GM sold 4,760,000 cars in the same period.[http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/new-cars/volkswagen-world%E2%80%99s-largest-car-maker-over-first-half-2016]\n\n-->\n\n== Literature ==\n* Jonas Kiefer: ''VW Typenatlas, Serienfahrzeuge.'' 2. Auflage. Delius Klasing, Bielefeld 2002, {{ISBN|3-7688-1271-5}}.\n* Rudi Heppe: ''VW Personenwagen.'' Podszun, Brilon 2001, {{ISBN|3-86133-209-4}}.\n* Halwart Schrader: ''VW Personenwagen seit 1945, Band 1, Typenkompass.'' Motorbuch Verlag, Stuttgart 2001, {{ISBN|3-613-02105-6}}.\n* Halwart Schrader: ''VW Personenwagen seit 1945, Band 2, Typenkompass.'' Motorbuch Verlag, Stuttgart 2001, {{ISBN|3-613-02186-2}}.\n* Werner Oswald: ''Deutsche Autos, Band 2, 1920\u20131945.'' 2. Auflage. Motorbuch Verlag, Stuttgart 2005, {{ISBN|3-613-02170-6}}.\n* Werner Oswald: ''Deutsche Autos, Band 3, 1945\u20131990, Ford, Opel und Volkswagen.'' 1. Auflage. Motorbuch Verlag, Stuttgart 2001, {{ISBN|3-613-02116-1}}.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Germany|Cars|Companies}}\n* [[Baja bug]]\n* [[Cal Look]]\n* [[Fahrvergn\u00fcgen]]\n* [[List of German cars]]\n* [[List of automobile manufacturers]]\n* [[Punch buggy]]\n* [[Standard Superior]]&nbsp;\u2013 a previous attempt to produce a \"Volkswagen\"\n* [[Steyr 50]]\n* [[Twin Drive]]\n* [[VDub]]&nbsp;\u2013 tagline for the recent VWoA Golf GTI TV advertisemen*\n* [[Volksflugzeug]]\n* [[Volksrod]]\n* [[Volkswagen advertising history]]\n* [[VW 276 Schlepperfahrzeug]], military use 1944\n* [[Volkswagen New Beetle]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=Note|colwidth=60em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=Spiegel>{{cite news\n| url=http://www.spiegel.de/einestages/apple-starbucks-coca-cola-vw-firmenlogos-und-ihre-geschichte-a-1073926.html\n| work=[[Der Spiegel]]\n| title=Das machen wir mal lieber neu\n| author=Christoph Stehr\n| date=2 February 2016\n| accessdate=7 February 2016\n| language=German\n| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207070212/http://www.spiegel.de/einestages/apple-starbucks-coca-cola-vw-firmenlogos-und-ihre-geschichte-a-1073926.html\n| archive-date=7 February 2016\n| url-status=live\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* William Shirer, The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich (50th Anniversary Edition) (New York: Simon & Schuster, 1990)\n* Andrea Hiott, Thinking Small (New York: Ballantine Books, 2012)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category multi|Volkswagen|Volkswagen vehicles}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180306133229/http://www.volkswagen.com/ Volkswagen.com] Volkswagen Cars Worldwide portal\n* [http://www.volkswagen-classic.de/ Volkswagen Classic] {{in lang|de}}\n* [http://www.thecaryoudrive.com/en/02175a425 Volkswagen Cars Technical Information]\n\n{{Volkswagen Group brands}}\n{{Volkswagen}}\n{{Volkswa