{"title_page": "Shirdi", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n:''Not to be confused with [[Shiradi]]''\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Shirdi\n| native_name             = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = Sainagar\n| settlement_type         = City\n| image_skyline           = Shirdi Sai Baba.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = [[Sai Baba of Shirdi]]\n| nickname                = Shirdi Nagari;<BR/>Sainagar Shirdi\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = India Maharashtra\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|19.77|N|74.48|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flagicon|IND}} [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Maharashtra]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Ahmednagar District|Ahmednagar]]\n|  established_title       = [[Taluka]]\n| established_date        = [[Rahata]]\n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = Seeradi\n| government_type         = Municipal Council\n| governing_body          = Shirdi Nagar Panchayat\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = 13\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 504\n| population_total        = 36004\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 423109\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 02423\n| registration_plate      = MH-17\n| website                 = {{URL|maharashtra.gov.in}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Shirdi''' {{audio|Shirdi.ogg|pronunciation}} also known as '''Sainagar''' is a city in the Indian state of Maharashtra. It is located in the [[Rahata taluka]] of [[Ahmednagar District]]. It is accessible via the Ahmednagar\u2013Malegaon State Highway No.10, approximately 83&nbsp;km from [[Ahmednagar]] and 15&nbsp;km from [[Kopargaon]]. It is located 185&nbsp;km east of the Western Seashore line (the Ahmednagar\u2013Manmad road), a very busy route.\n\nShirdi is famously known as the home of the late 19th century [[saint]] Shri [[Sai Baba of Shirdi|Sai Baba]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shirdi|url=http://www.amazingmaharashtra.com/2012/05/shirdi.html|publisher=Amazing Maharashtra}}</ref> The Shri Saibaba Sansthan Trust located in Shirdi is one of the richest temple organisations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/india-top-10-richest-temples-27684.html|title=India's top 10 richest temples|date=2013-09-10|website=www.indiatvnews.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nAs of the 2011 India [[census]], the population of Shirdi stood at 36,004. Males constitute 53% of the population and females 47%. Shirdi has an average literacy rate of 70%, higher than the national average of 59.5%: male literacy is 76%, and female literacy is 62%. In Shirdi, 15% of the population is under 6 years of age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\n\n=== Train ===\nThe [[Sainagar Shirdi Railway Station|Sainagar Shirdi Railway station]] became operational in March 2009. As of 2011, there are trains from [[Chennai]],<ref name=\"newtrainsjuly\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/article2146173.ece|title=New trains will start operations from July|date=2011-06-30|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"cbetutexp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article2149345.ece|title=Coimbatore-Tuticorin Express service from today|date=2011-07-01|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=27 April 2012|location=Tuticorin}}</ref> [[Mumbai]], [[Visakhapatnam]], [[Kakinada]], [[Hyderabad]] [[Mysore]]<ref name=\"mysoreweekly\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hubli/Mysore-Shirdi-weekly-train-from-Aug-1/articleshow/9413259.cms|title=Mysore-Shirdi weekly train from Aug 1|date=2011-07-29|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=27 April 2012|location=Hubli}}</ref> and other cities/states that have Shirdi railway station as their terminal stop.\nHowever very few weekly and biweekly trains are available from Shirdi station.\n\nPeoples use Kopargaon Railway station (18 Kms apart)to reach Shirdi. Trains which do not go to shirdi, have halts at Kopargaon from last 2 decades. Trains to all over India can be taken from Kopargaon Station.\nManmad is also accesible from shirdi by 60 Kms road travel.\n\n=== Air ===\n[[Shirdi Airport]] was inaugurated by the President of India, [[Ram Nath Kovind|Ramnath Kovind]], on 1 October 2017. There are major destinations from Shirdi airport, viz. the airports of Delhi, Hyderabad, Chennai and Mumbai. The airport is located at Kakdi ([[Kopargaon taluka]]), 14&nbsp;km south-west of Shirdi.<ref>{{cite news| title=Shirdi airport work in full swing: Official |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-07-02/pune/28275574_1_shirdi-airport-airport-project-airport-for-devotees-planning|accessdate=3 June 2012|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|date=2 July 2010}}</ref> The construction, according to the original plans, was completed in February 2016, and the first trial flight landed on 2 March 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=First trial flight touches down at Shirdi airport |author=Yogesh Naik |url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/mumbai/others/First-trial-flight-touches-down-at-Shirdi-airport/articleshow/51232066.cms |newspaper=[[Mumbai Mirror]] |date=3 March 2016 |accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> There are plans to lengthen the runway from 2,200 metres to 3,200 metres. The target completion date is 2017 or 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Maharashtra govt made the runway for Shirdi Airport in 2013, rest of it will be made in 2017! |author=Kunal Anand |url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/maharashtra-govt-made-the-runway-for-shirdi-airport-in-2013-rest-of-it-will-be-made-in-2017_-250528.html |newspaper=[[India Times]] |date=10 February 2016 |accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe nearest major airports are at [[Aurangabad Airport|Aurangabad]] and [[Pune Airport|Pune]], 115&nbsp;km and 186&nbsp;km respectively from Shirdi.\n\n=== By car ===\nShirdi is accessible via the Ahmednagar-Manmad State Highway No.10, approximately 83&nbsp;km from Ahmednagar and 15&nbsp;km from Kopargaon. It is approximately 240&nbsp;km from Mumbai on the Eastern Express Highway. The distance between Pune and Shirdi is about 204&nbsp;km, and travel time via car is about 3 hours 40 minutes.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Shirdi}}\n*Read [https://ebhajanlyrics.com/category/sai-bhajans/sai-bhajans-in-english/ Sai Bhajans In English]\n\n{{Ahmednagar district topics}}\n\n[[Category:Talukas in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Articles containing potentially dated statements from 2001]]\n[[Category:All articles containing potentially dated statements]]\n[[Category:Hindu holy cities]]\n[[Category:Shirdi]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Ahmednagar district]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n:''Not to be confused with [[Shiradi]]''\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Shirdi\n| native_name             = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = Sainagar\n| settlement_type         = City\n| image_skyline           = Shirdi Sai Baba.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = [[Sai Baba of Shirdi]]\n| nickname                = Shirdi Nagari;<BR/>Sainagar Shirdi\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = India Maharashtra\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|19.77|N|74.48|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flagicon|IND}} [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Maharashtra]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Ahmednagar District|Ahmednagar]]\n|  established_title       = [[Taluka]]\n| established_date        = [[Rahata]]\n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = Seeradi\n| government_type         = Municipal Council\n| governing_body          = Shirdi Nagar Panchayat\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = 13\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 504\n| population_total        = 36004\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 423109\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 02423\n| registration_plate      = MH-17\n| website                 = {{URL|maharashtra.gov.in}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Shirdi''' {{audio|Shirdi.ogg|pronunciation}} also known as '''Sainagar''' is a city in the Indian state of Maharashtra. It is located in the [[Rahata taluka]] of [[Ahmednagar District]]. It is accessible via the Ahmednagar\u2013Malegaon State Highway No.10, approximately 83&nbsp;km from [[Ahmednagar]] and 15&nbsp;km from [[Kopargaon]]. It is located 185&nbsp;km east of the Western Seashore line (the Ahmednagar\u2013Manmad road), a very busy route.\n\nShirdi is famously known as the home of the late 19th century [[saint]] Shri [[Sai Baba of Shirdi|Sai Baba]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shirdi|url=http://www.amazingmaharashtra.com/2012/05/shirdi.html|publisher=Amazing Maharashtra}}</ref> The Shri Saibaba Sansthan Trust located in Shirdi is one of the richest temple organisations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/india-top-10-richest-temples-27684.html|title=India's top 10 richest temples|date=2013-09-10|website=www.indiatvnews.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nAs of the 2011 India [[census]], the population of Shirdi stood at 36,004. Males constitute 53% of the population and females 47%. Shirdi has an average literacy rate of 70%, higher than the national average of 59.5%: male literacy is 76%, and female literacy is 62%. In Shirdi, 15% of the population is under 6 years of age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref>\n\n== Transport ==\n\n=== Train ===\nThe [[Sainagar Shirdi Railway Station|Sainagar Shirdi Railway station]] became operational in March 2009. As of 2011, there are trains from [[Chennai]],<ref name=\"newtrainsjuly\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/article2146173.ece|title=New trains will start operations from July|date=2011-06-30|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"cbetutexp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article2149345.ece|title=Coimbatore-Tuticorin Express service from today|date=2011-07-01|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|accessdate=27 April 2012|location=Tuticorin}}</ref> [[Mumbai]], [[Visakhapatnam]], [[Kakinada]], [[Hyderabad]] [[Mysore]]<ref name=\"mysoreweekly\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hubli/Mysore-Shirdi-weekly-train-from-Aug-1/articleshow/9413259.cms|title=Mysore-Shirdi weekly train from Aug 1|date=2011-07-29|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=27 April 2012|location=Hubli}}</ref> and other cities/states that have Shirdi railway station as their terminal stop.\nHowever very few weekly and biweekly trains are available from Shirdi station.\n\nPeoples use Kopargaon Railway station (18 Kms apart)to reach Shirdi. Trains which do not go to shirdi, have halts at Kopargaon from last 2 decades. Trains to all over India can be taken from Kopargaon Station.\nManmad is also accesible from shirdi by 60 Kms road travel.\n\n=== Air ===\n[[Shirdi Airport]] was inaugurated by the President of India, [[Ram Nath Kovind|Ramnath Kovind]], on 1 October 2017. There are major destinations from Shirdi airport, viz. the airports of Delhi, Hyderabad, Chennai and Mumbai. The airport is located at Kakdi ([[Kopargaon taluka]]), 14&nbsp;km south-west of Shirdi.<ref>{{cite news| title=Shirdi airport work in full swing: Official |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-07-02/pune/28275574_1_shirdi-airport-airport-project-airport-for-devotees-planning|accessdate=3 June 2012|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|date=2 July 2010}}</ref> The construction, according to the original plans, was completed in February 2016, and the first trial flight landed on 2 March 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=First trial flight touches down at Shirdi airport |author=Yogesh Naik |url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/mumbai/others/First-trial-flight-touches-down-at-Shirdi-airport/articleshow/51232066.cms |newspaper=[[Mumbai Mirror]] |date=3 March 2016 |accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> There are plans to lengthen the runway from 2,200 metres to 3,200 metres. The target completion date is 2017 or 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Maharashtra govt made the runway for Shirdi Airport in 2013, rest of it will be made in 2017! |author=Kunal Anand |url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/maharashtra-govt-made-the-runway-for-shirdi-airport-in-2013-rest-of-it-will-be-made-in-2017_-250528.html |newspaper=[[India Times]] |date=10 February 2016 |accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe nearest major airports are at [[Aurangabad Airport|Aurangabad]] and [[Pune Airport|Pune]], 115&nbsp;km and 186&nbsp;km respectively from Shirdi.\n\n=== By car ===\nShirdi is accessible via the Ahmednagar-Manmad State Highway No.10, approximately 83&nbsp;km from Ahmednagar and 15&nbsp;km from Kopargaon. It is approximately 240&nbsp;km from Mumbai on the Eastern Express Highway. The distance between Pune and Shirdi is about 204&nbsp;km, and travel time via car is about 3 hours 40 minutes.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Shirdi}}\n\n{{Ahmednagar district topics}}\n\n[[Category:Talukas in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Articles containing potentially dated statements from 2001]]\n[[Category:All articles containing potentially dated statements]]\n[[Category:Hindu holy cities]]\n[[Category:Shirdi]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Ahmednagar district]]\n", "name_user": "Wadhwayugal", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:i have added link on which user can click to read the bhajan of sai in english", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shirdi"}
{"title_page": "Tom Moore (fundraiser)", "text_new": "{{short description|British Army Officer and fundraiser}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n| name               = Tom Moore\n| image              = Tom Moore (soldier).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Moore during his military service\n| birth_name         = Thomas Moore\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Keighley]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]], United Kingdom\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = British\n| residence          = [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]]\n| education          = \n| alma mater         = \n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Army officer\n* Managing director \n}}\n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| known for          = {{Plainlist|\n* Second World War veteran\n* 2020 fundraising walk\n}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Keighley Grammar School]], West Yorkshire\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| website            = {{URL|https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|tomswalkforthenhs}}\n| module = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n   | allegiance  = {{GBR}}\n   |branch       = {{flagicon image|Flag of the British Army (1938-present).png}} [[British Army]]\n   |serviceyears = 1939\u20131946\n   |rank         = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n   |unit         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]\n* [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n* [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n}}\n   |commands     = \n   |battles           = {{tree list}}\n*[[World War II|Second World War]]\n**[[Burma campaign 1944\u201345|Burma Campaign]]\n***[[Battle of Ramree Island]]\n   |awards = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Thomas Moore''' (born 30 April 1920), known as '''Captain Tom''', is a former [[British Army]] officer, best known for his philanthropic work. Moore served in India and the [[Burma campaign]] during the [[Second World War]]. He later became an instructor in [[armoured warfare]]. After the war, he worked as managing director of a concrete company and was an avid motorcycle racer. On 6 April 2020, at the age of 99, he began to walk around his garden in aid of [[NHS Charities Together]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]], with the goal of raising \u00a31,000 by his hundredth birthday on 30 April. By 18 April he had raised over \u00a325.6<!-- please update the figure in two places, and the date/timestamp -->&nbsp;million, and a further \u00a34.8 million in [[Gift Aid]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Early life and family==\n\nMoore was born to Wilfred, one of a family of builders, in [[Keighley]], in the former [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], on 30 April 1920 and was raised in the town.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Faye |title=The story behind the 99-year-old legend who raised \u00a314m for the NHS |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/16/tom-moore-story-behind-14000000-nhs-legend-12565964/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strayfm.com/news/local-news/3082429/coronavirus-veteran-from-keighley-raises-over-2-million-for-nhs/|title=Coronavirus: Veteran from Keighley raises over \u00a32 MILLION for NHS|date=14 April 2020|publisher=Stray FM|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/14/war-veteran-99-raises-2m-for-nhs-by-walking-lengths-of-back-garden|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36m for NHS by walking lengths of back garden|first=Jessica|last=Murray|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He was educated at [[Keighley Grammar School]] and completed an apprenticeship in [[civil engineering]].<ref name=\"Nicholls\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/14/second-world-war-veteran-raises-2-million-nhs/ |title=Second World War veteran raises more than \u00a33m for NHS |first=Dominic |last=Nicholls |date=14 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nMoore  enlisted in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment#8th Battalion|8th Battalion, Duke of Wellington's Regiment]] (8 DWR) at the beginning of the [[Second World War]], stationed in [[Cornwall]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> He was selected for officer training in 1940,<ref name=\"Nicholls\" />  and attended an Officer Cadet Training Unit before being commissioned as a [[second lieutenant#United Kingdom & other Commonwealth countries|second lieutenant]] on 28 June 1941.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35218|date=11 July 1941|page=4057|supp=y}}</ref>\n\nMoore became a member of the [[Royal Armoured Corps]] on 22 October 1941 when his battalion, the 8 DWR, became an armoured unit, designated as the [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35740|date=9 October 1942|page=4432|supp=y}}</ref><ref name=\"Nicholls\"/> Later he was transferred to the 9th Battalion (9 DWR) in India, which had also been redesignated as the [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]. He was initially posted to [[Bombay]] and subsequently to [[Calcutta]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> His regiment were equipped with [[M3 Lee]] tanks and participated in the [[Battle of Ramree Island]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whiting |first1=Charles |last2=Taylor |first2=Eric |date=2008 |title=The Fighting Tykes: An Informal History of the Yorkshire Regiments in the Second World War |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9kt-AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA132 |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |page=132 |isbn=978-1844156450}}</ref> He was promoted to war-substantive [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 1 October 1942 and to temporary [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 11 October 1944.<ref>{{cite book |date=1946 |title=The Quarterly Army List (August 1946 \u2013 Part I) |location=London |publisher=HM Stationery Office |isbn= |pages=385a |url=https://archive.org/details/armylistaugpart121946grea/page/398/mode/2up|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe served in [[Arakan Campaign 1942\u201343|Arakan]] in western Burma and afterward in [[Sumatra]] after the Japanese surrendered,<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52278746|title=Army veteran, 99, raises \u00a34m for 'humbled' NHS|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> by which time he had risen to the rank of captain.<ref name=\"Nicholls\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/> On his return to Britain he served as an instructor at the Armoured Fighting Vehicle School in [[Bovington Camp|Bovington]], Dorset.<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/>\n\n=== Decorations ===\nDuring his war service, Moore was awarded three medals:<ref name=\"ES\">{{cite news |title=War veteran, 99, hits \u00a314m for NHS as Hancock calls him an inspiration |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/war-veteran-tom-moore-matt-hancock-9-million-nhs-a4415496.html |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n*[[1939\u20131945 Star]]\n*[[Burma Star]]\n*[[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]\n\n== Later work and hobbies ==\n\nAfter leaving the army, he worked as managing director of a company manufacturing [[concrete]].<ref name=\"Spary\" />\n\nFor 64 years he organised the DWR's annual reunion.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\nMoore raced motorcycles competitively, wearing the number 23.<ref name=\"Hancocks\">{{cite web |last1=Hancocks |first1=Simon |title=Veteran NHS fundraiser Captain Tom Moore was also a motorcycle racer |url=https://www.visordown.com/news/general/veteran-nhs-fundraiser-captain-tom-moore-was-also-motorcycle-racer |website=Visordown |accessdate=17 April 2020 }}</ref> He rode a [[The Scott Motorcycle Company|Scott motorcycle]], winning several trophies.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\n== Tom's 100th Birthday Walk  ==\n[[File:Captain Tom Moore fundraising walk.jpg|thumb|upright|Moore during the fund-raising initiative walk. He is wearing the [[1939\u20131945 Star]], [[Burma Star]], and [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]. |alt=Moore wearing a blazer with regimental badge, regimental tie and three medals]]\n\nOn 6 April 2020 he began a fundraising campaign to raise money for [[NHS Charities Together]], a group of charities supporting staff and volunteers caring for COVID-19 patients in the British public health services during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] by aiming to complete one hundred {{convert|25|m|yard|abbr=on}} laps of his garden, ten laps per day, with the help of a [[Walker (mobility)|walking frame]], branding the endeavour \"'''Tom's 100th Birthday Walk For The NHS'''\".<ref name=\"Spary\" /><ref name=\"Low\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52290976\">{{cite web |title=Army veteran's \u00a37m for NHS 'out of this world' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52290976 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe initial \u00a31,000 goal having been realised on Friday 10 April, the target was increased, first to \u00a35,000, and eventually to \u00a3500,000 as more people around the world became involved.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/nhs-100-birthday-walk-army-veteran-tom-moore-fundraise-a9463561.html |title=99-year-old army veteran raises more than \u00a31m for NHS with \u2018100th birthday walk\u2019 |date=14 April 2020 |work=The Independent |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> The fund-raising soared exponentially when the British media publicised the endeavour. Moore, who joined [[Twitter]] in the same month, used the site to express joy over accumulating such a staggering amount of money for the NHS.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=CaptainTomMoore |number=1250418629218168833 |date=15 April 2020 |title=7 MILLION POUNDS!!!! The Great British public, your generosity is just incredible! THANK YOU!! }}</ref> \n\nThe [[JustGiving]] page for his walk reports that, as of 09:30 19 April 2020 (UTC), he had raised in excess of \u00a325.6<!-- please update the figure in two places, and the date/ timestamp-->&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"JGTM\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs |publisher=[[JustGiving]] |accessdate=18 April 2020 }}</ref> the largest-ever amount raised by a JustGiving campaign,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |website=inews.co.uk| access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-18098819|title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard|last=Shaw|first=Neil|date=2020-04-16|website=walesonline|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> beating the previous record of \u00a35.2&nbsp;million raised (partially posthumously) by [[Stephen Sutton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen's fundraising page |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/stephen-sutton-tct |website=JustGiving |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Butterworth\">{{cite news |last1=Butterworth |first1=Benjamin |title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=inews.co.uk }}</ref> More than 1.1 million individuals have donated.<ref name=\"JGTM\" />\n\nFunds raised by Moore are being spent on such things as well-being packs for National Health Service staff facilitating rest and recuperation rooms, devices to enable hospital patients to keep in contact with family members, and community groups who support patients once discharged from hospitals.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52325713\">{{cite web |last1=Shepka |first1=Phil |last2=Lewis |first2=Katy |title=How will Captain Tom Moore's millions be spent? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52325713 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe achieved his initial target of one hundred laps on the morning of 16 April, watched [[Social distancing measures related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|at a safe distance]] by a [[guard of honour]] from the [[1st Battalion, The Yorkshire Regiment|1st Battalion of the Yorkshire Regiment]],<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Neil |title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard |url=https://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-4050824 |work=hulldailymail |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> into which the DWR were merged in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx |title=The Yorkshire Regiment |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence]] |archivedate=27 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527064813/http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx }}</ref> He has said he will not stop, and aims to do a second hundred.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" />\n\nOn reaching the \u00a35&nbsp;million mark, Moore explained his motivation:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-52296313/coronavirus-army-veteran-tom-moore-finds-out-he-s-raised-5m-for-nhs |title=Army veteran, 99, finds out he's raised \u00a35m for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When we started off with this exercise we didn't anticipate we'd get anything near that sort of money. It's really amazing. All of them, from top to bottom, in the National Health Service, they deserve everything that we can possibly put in their place. They're all so brave. Because every morning or every night they're putting themselves into harm's way, and I think you've got to give them full marks for that effort. We're a little bit like having a war at the moment. But the doctors and the nurses, they're all on the front line, and all of us behind, we've got to supply them and keep them going with everything that they need, so that they can do their jobs even better than they're doing now.}}\n\n=== Charity recording ===\n\nTo mark Moore's 100th lap, the singer [[Michael Ball]] has recorded a version of \"[[You'll Never Walk Alone]]\", with the NHS Voices of Care Choir. Moore provides spoken words.<ref name=\"ITV\">{{cite news |title=Captain Tom Moore launches You'll Never Walk Alone charity single with Michael Ball |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-18/captain-tom-moore-launches-you-ll-never-walk-alone-charity-single-with-michael-ball/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=ITV News }}</ref> The recording has been released as a digital single by Decca Records.<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web |title=You'll Never Walk Alone - Single by Michael Ball, Captain Tom Moore & The NHS Voices of Care Choir |url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/youll-never-walk-alone/1508494673?i=1508494683&uo=2 |publisher=Apple Music |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\n\nMoore has given well over 50 media interviews.<ref name=\"BBC-52333127\">{{cite web |title=Capt Tom 'speechless' as fundraising passes \u00a323m |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52333127 |website=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, after Moore's 100th lap, a UK Government spokesman said:<ref name=\"Lovett\">{{cite news |last1=Lovett |first1=Samuel |title=UK death toll rises again as lockdown to be extended \u2013 follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-news-live-update-latest-today-cases-deaths-lockdown-covid-19-a9467756.html#post-1187989853 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The Prime Minister will certainly be looking at ways to recognise Tom's heroic efforts.}}\n\nBy mid-day on 17 April, more than 505,000 people had signed a petition calling for him to be knighted.<ref name=\"BBC-52321262\">{{cite news |title=Prince William hails veteran's \u00a318m NHS fundraiser |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52321262 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBrigadier Andrew Jackson, colonel of the Yorkshire Regiment, described Moore as:<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\">{{cite web |title=Capt Tom to be guest of honour at hospital opening |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-52340554 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|an absolute legend [from] an exceptional generation that are still an inspiration for our Yorkshire soldiers today.}}\n\nMoore has also been invited to be guest of honour, via a video link, when [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Yorkshire and the Humber]], in [[Harrogate]], is formally opened on 21 April.<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\" />\n\n===Similar fundraising efforts===\nMoore's success inspired retired Welsh farmer Rhythwyn Evans to launch his own fundraising campaign<ref name=\"JGDE\">{{cite web|title=Her 91 dros COVID-19 Rhythwyn|url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/david-evans186|quote=91st birthday challenge to support local NHS staff for Hywel Dda Health Charities because of their hard work during COVID-19|publisher=Just Giving|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> by walking 91 laps of his bungalow in [[Silian, Ceredigion|Silian]], [[Ceredigion]], before his 91st birthday. Evans said that his walk was \"inspired by and in solidarity with Captain Tom Moore\" and that he aimed to raise \u00a31,000 for his local health board \"to give something back to the community\", having lived to a \"ripe old age\". As of 14:30, 18 April 2020 (UTC), Evans has raised over \u00a312,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/uk-news/2020/04/18/grandfather-walks-91-laps-around-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-to-raise-cash-for-nhs/ |title=Grandfather walks 91 laps around bungalow on 91st birthday to raise cash for NHS|publisher=Shropshire Star|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-52333077/coronavirus-capt-tom-moore-inspires-91-year-old-s-walk-for-nhs|title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore inspires 91-year-old's walk for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=17 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMoore married Pamela in 1968,<ref name=\"Lavender\">{{cite news |last1=Lavender |first1=Jane |title=Captain Tom Moore had 'given up on love' before he met beloved late wife aged 50 |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-given-up-21876074 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=mirror |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> and they had two daughters.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> Pamela died circa 2006.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> He has lived with one of his daughters, Hannah, her husband, and two grandchildren, in [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]] since 2008.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /> He also has two other grandchildren.<ref name=\"Brown\" /> In recent years he has received treatment from the NHS for skin cancer and, in 2018, a broken hip.<ref name=\"Brown\" /><ref name=\"Low\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/captain-tom-moore-99-walks-to-raise-millions-for-the-nhs-fzpn0cjfb|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, raises \u00a35m for NHS with 100th birthday walk|first=Valentine|last=Low|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/99-year-old-army-veteran-raises-2-million-charity-walking-his-backyard-1497742|title=99-year-old army veteran raises $2 million for charity by walking in his backyard|first=Khaleda | last=Rahman|date=14 April 2020|website=Newsweek|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spary\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/world/war-veteran-raises-millions-garden-scli-intl-gbr/index.html|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36 million by walking laps of his garden|first=Sara |last=Spary|website=CNN|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs Moore's fund-raising page]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{YouTube|wUP-ty-Tj5E|You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52316856 Captain Tom Moore: How the war veteran captured our hearts] \u2013 BBC news\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Tom}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Duke of Wellington's Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:English civil engineers]]\n[[Category:People from Keighley]]\n[[Category:Skin cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Royal Armoured Corps officers]]\n[[Category:English motorcycle racers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Army Officer and fundraiser}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n| name               = Tom Moore\n| image              = Tom Moore (soldier).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Moore during his military service\n| birth_name         = Thomas Moore\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1920|4|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Keighley]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]], United Kingdom\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = British\n| residence          = [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]]\n| education          = \n| alma mater         = \n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Army officer\n* Managing director \n}}\n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| known for          = {{Plainlist|\n* Second World War veteran\n* 2020 fundraising walk\n}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Keighley Grammar School]], West Yorkshire\n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| website            = {{URL|https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|tomswalkforthenhs}}\n| module = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n   | allegiance  = {{GBR}}\n   |branch       = {{flagicon image|Flag of the British Army (1938-present).png}} [[British Army]]\n   |serviceyears = 1939\u20131946\n   |rank         = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n   |unit         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]\n* [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n* [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]\n}}\n   |commands     = \n   |battles           = {{tree list}}\n*[[World War II|Second World War]]\n**[[Burma campaign 1944\u201345|Burma Campaign]]\n***[[Battle of Ramree Island]]\n   |awards = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Thomas Moore''' (born 30 April 1920), known as '''Captain Tom''', is a former [[British Army]] officer, best known for his philanthropic work. Moore served in India and the [[Burma campaign]] during the [[Second World War]]. He later became an instructor in [[armoured warfare]]. After the war, he worked as managing director of a concrete company and was an avid motorcycle racer. On 6 April 2020, at the age of 99, he began to walk around his garden in aid of [[NHS Charities Together]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]], with the goal of raising \u00a31,000 by his hundredth birthday on 30 April. By 18 April he had raised over \u00a325.6<!-- please update the figure in two places, and the date/timestamp -->&nbsp;million, and a further \u00a34.8 million in [[Gift Aid]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Early life and family==\n\nMoore was born to Wilfred, one of a family of builders, in [[Keighley]], in the former [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], on 30 April 1920 and was raised in the town.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Faye |title=The story behind the 99-year-old legend who raised \u00a314m for the NHS |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/16/tom-moore-story-behind-14000000-nhs-legend-12565964/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strayfm.com/news/local-news/3082429/coronavirus-veteran-from-keighley-raises-over-2-million-for-nhs/|title=Coronavirus: Veteran from Keighley raises over \u00a32 MILLION for NHS|date=14 April 2020|publisher=Stray FM|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/14/war-veteran-99-raises-2m-for-nhs-by-walking-lengths-of-back-garden|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36m for NHS by walking lengths of back garden|first=Jessica|last=Murray|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Guardian}}</ref> He was educated at [[Keighley Grammar School]] and completed an apprenticeship in [[civil engineering]].<ref name=\"Nicholls\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/14/second-world-war-veteran-raises-2-million-nhs/ |title=Second World War veteran raises more than \u00a33m for NHS |first=Dominic |last=Nicholls |date=14 April 2020 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nMoore  enlisted in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment#8th Battalion|8th Battalion, Duke of Wellington's Regiment]] (8 DWR) at the beginning of the [[Second World War]], stationed in [[Cornwall]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> He was selected for officer training in 1940,<ref name=\"Nicholls\" />  and attended an Officer Cadet Training Unit before being commissioned as a [[second lieutenant#United Kingdom & other Commonwealth countries|second lieutenant]] on 28 June 1941.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35218|date=11 July 1941|page=4057|supp=y}}</ref>\n\nMoore became a member of the [[Royal Armoured Corps]] on 22 October 1941 when his battalion, the 8 DWR, became an armoured unit, designated as the [[145th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35740|date=9 October 1942|page=4432|supp=y}}</ref><ref name=\"Nicholls\"/> Later he was transferred to the 9th Battalion (9 DWR) in India, which had also been redesignated as the [[146th Regiment Royal Armoured Corps]]. He was initially posted to [[Bombay]] and subsequently to [[Calcutta]].<ref name=\"Brown\" /> His regiment were equipped with [[M3 Lee]] tanks and participated in the [[Battle of Ramree Island]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whiting |first1=Charles |last2=Taylor |first2=Eric |date=2008 |title=The Fighting Tykes: An Informal History of the Yorkshire Regiments in the Second World War |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9kt-AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA132 |publisher=Pen & Sword Military |page=132 |isbn=978-1844156450}}</ref> He was promoted to war-substantive [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 1 October 1942 and to temporary [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 11 October 1944.<ref>{{cite book |date=1946 |title=The Quarterly Army List (August 1946 \u2013 Part I) |location=London |publisher=HM Stationery Office |isbn= |pages=385a |url=https://archive.org/details/armylistaugpart121946grea/page/398/mode/2up|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe served in [[Arakan Campaign 1942\u201343|Arakan]] in western Burma and afterward in [[Sumatra]] after the Japanese surrendered,<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52278746|title=Army veteran, 99, raises \u00a34m for 'humbled' NHS|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> by which time he had risen to the rank of captain.<ref name=\"Nicholls\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/> On his return to Britain he served as an instructor at the Armoured Fighting Vehicle School in [[Bovington Camp|Bovington]], Dorset.<ref name=\"Nicholls\"/><ref name=\"BBC-52278746\"/>\n\n=== Decorations ===\nDuring his war service, Moore was awarded three medals:<ref name=\"ES\">{{cite news |title=War veteran, 99, hits \u00a314m for NHS as Hancock calls him an inspiration |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/war-veteran-tom-moore-matt-hancock-9-million-nhs-a4415496.html |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n*[[1939\u20131945 Star]]\n*[[Burma Star]]\n*[[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]\n\n== Later work and hobbies ==\n\nAfter leaving the army, he worked as managing director of a company manufacturing [[concrete]].<ref name=\"Spary\" />\n\nFor 64 years he organised the DWR's annual reunion.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\nMoore raced motorcycles competitively, wearing the number 23.<ref name=\"Hancocks\">{{cite web |last1=Hancocks |first1=Simon |title=Veteran NHS fundraiser Captain Tom Moore was also a motorcycle racer |url=https://www.visordown.com/news/general/veteran-nhs-fundraiser-captain-tom-moore-was-also-motorcycle-racer |website=Visordown |accessdate=17 April 2020 }}</ref> He rode a [[The Scott Motorcycle Company|Scott motorcycle]], winning several trophies.<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n\n== Tom's 100th Birthday Walk  ==\n[[File:Captain Tom Moore fundraising walk.jpg|thumb|upright|Moore during the fund-raising initiative walk. He is wearing the [[1939\u20131945 Star]], [[Burma Star]], and [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]]. |alt=Moore wearing a blazer with regimental badge, regimental tie and three medals]]\n\nOn 6 April 2020 he began a fundraising campaign to raise money for [[NHS Charities Together]], a group of charities supporting staff and volunteers caring for COVID-19 patients in the British public health services during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] by aiming to complete one hundred {{convert|25|m|yard|abbr=on}} laps of his garden, ten laps per day, with the help of a [[Walker (mobility)|walking frame]], branding the endeavour \"'''Tom's 100th Birthday Walk For The NHS'''\".<ref name=\"Spary\" /><ref name=\"Low\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52290976\">{{cite web |title=Army veteran's \u00a37m for NHS 'out of this world' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52290976 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe initial \u00a31,000 goal having been realised on Friday 10 April, the target was increased, first to \u00a35,000, and eventually to \u00a3500,000 as more people around the world became involved.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/nhs-100-birthday-walk-army-veteran-tom-moore-fundraise-a9463561.html |title=99-year-old army veteran raises more than \u00a31m for NHS with \u2018100th birthday walk\u2019 |date=14 April 2020 |work=The Independent |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> The fund-raising soared exponentially when the British media publicised the endeavour. Moore, who joined [[Twitter]] in the same month, used the site to express joy over accumulating such a staggering amount of money for the NHS.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=CaptainTomMoore |number=1250418629218168833 |date=15 April 2020 |title=7 MILLION POUNDS!!!! The Great British public, your generosity is just incredible! THANK YOU!! }}</ref> \n\nThe [[JustGiving]] page for his walk reports that, as of 09:30 19 April 2020 (UTC), he had raised in excess of \u00a325.6<!-- please update the figure in two places, and the date/ timestamp-->&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"JGTM\">{{cite web |title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs |publisher=[[JustGiving]] |accessdate=18 April 2020 }}</ref> the largest-ever amount raised by a JustGiving campaign,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |website=inews.co.uk| access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-18098819|title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard|last=Shaw|first=Neil|date=2020-04-16|website=walesonline|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> beating the previous record of \u00a35.2&nbsp;million raised (partially posthumously) by [[Stephen Sutton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen's fundraising page |url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/stephen-sutton-tct |website=JustGiving |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Butterworth\">{{cite news |last1=Butterworth |first1=Benjamin |title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, breaks all time charity fundraising record with NHS walk |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/captain-tom-moore-just-giving-nhs-fundraiser-record-charity-2539792 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=inews.co.uk }}</ref> More than 1.1 million individuals have donated.<ref name=\"JGTM\" />\n\nFunds raised by Moore are being spent on such things as well-being packs for National Health Service staff facilitating rest and recuperation rooms, devices to enable hospital patients to keep in contact with family members, and community groups who support patients once discharged from hospitals.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52325713\">{{cite web |last1=Shepka |first1=Phil |last2=Lewis |first2=Katy |title=How will Captain Tom Moore's millions be spent? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52325713 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe achieved his initial target of one hundred laps on the morning of 16 April, watched [[Social distancing measures related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|at a safe distance]] by a [[guard of honour]] from the [[1st Battalion, The Yorkshire Regiment|1st Battalion of the Yorkshire Regiment]],<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Neil |title=Captain Tom Moore completes \u00a312m walk for NHS with honour guard |url=https://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/captain-tom-moore-completes-12m-4050824 |work=hulldailymail |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> into which the DWR were merged in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx |title=The Yorkshire Regiment |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence]] |archivedate=27 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527064813/http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/23987.aspx }}</ref> He has said he will not stop, and aims to do a second hundred.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" />\n\nOn reaching the \u00a35&nbsp;million mark, Moore explained his motivation:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-52296313/coronavirus-army-veteran-tom-moore-finds-out-he-s-raised-5m-for-nhs |title=Army veteran, 99, finds out he's raised \u00a35m for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=15 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When we started off with this exercise we didn't anticipate we'd get anything near that sort of money. It's really amazing. All of them, from top to bottom, in the National Health Service, they deserve everything that we can possibly put in their place. They're all so brave. Because every morning or every night they're putting themselves into harm's way, and I think you've got to give them full marks for that effort. We're a little bit like having a war at the moment. But the doctors and the nurses, they're all on the front line, and all of us behind, we've got to supply them and keep them going with everything that they need, so that they can do their jobs even better than they're doing now.}}\n\n=== Charity recording ===\n\nTo mark Moore's 100th lap, the singer [[Michael Ball]] has recorded a version of \"[[You'll Never Walk Alone]]\", with the NHS Voices of Care Choir. Moore provides spoken words.<ref name=\"ITV\">{{cite news |title=Captain Tom Moore launches You'll Never Walk Alone charity single with Michael Ball |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-18/captain-tom-moore-launches-you-ll-never-walk-alone-charity-single-with-michael-ball/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=ITV News }}</ref> The recording has been released as a digital single by Decca Records.<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web |title=You'll Never Walk Alone - Single by Michael Ball, Captain Tom Moore & The NHS Voices of Care Choir |url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/youll-never-walk-alone/1508494673?i=1508494683&uo=2 |publisher=Apple Music |accessdate=19 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\n\nMoore has given well over 50 media interviews.<ref name=\"BBC-52333127\">{{cite web |title=Capt Tom 'speechless' as fundraising passes \u00a323m |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52333127 |website=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, after Moore's 100th lap, a UK Government spokesman said:<ref name=\"Lovett\">{{cite news |last1=Lovett |first1=Samuel |title=UK death toll rises again as lockdown to be extended \u2013 follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-news-live-update-latest-today-cases-deaths-lockdown-covid-19-a9467756.html#post-1187989853 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=16 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The Prime Minister will certainly be looking at ways to recognise Tom's heroic efforts.}}\n\nBy mid-day on 17 April, more than 505,000 people had signed a petition calling for him to be knighted.<ref name=\"BBC-52321262\">{{cite news |title=Prince William hails veteran's \u00a318m NHS fundraiser |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52321262 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBrigadier Andrew Jackson, colonel of the Yorkshire Regiment, described Moore as:<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\">{{cite web |title=Capt Tom to be guest of honour at hospital opening |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-52340554 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|an absolute legend [from] an exceptional generation that are still an inspiration for our Yorkshire soldiers today.}}\n\nMoore has also been invited to be guest of honour, via a video link, when [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Yorkshire and the Humber]], in [[Harrogate]], is formally opened on 21 April.<ref name=\"BBC-52340554\" />\n\n===Similar fundraising efforts===\nMoore's success inspired retired Welsh farmer Rhythwyn Evans to launch his own fundraising campaign<ref name=\"JGDE\">{{cite web|title=Her 91 dros COVID-19 Rhythwyn|url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/david-evans186|quote=91st birthday challenge to support local NHS staff for Hywel Dda Health Charities because of their hard work during COVID-19|publisher=Just Giving|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> by walking 91 laps of his bungalow in [[Silian, Ceredigion|Silian]], [[Ceredigion]], before his 91st birthday. Evans said that his walk was \"inspired by and in solidarity with Captain Tom Moore\" and that he aimed to raise \u00a31,000 for his local health board \"to give something back to the community\", having lived to a \"ripe old age\". As of 14:30, 18 April 2020 (UTC), Evans has raised over \u00a312,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/uk-news/2020/04/18/grandfather-walks-91-laps-around-bungalow-on-91st-birthday-to-raise-cash-for-nhs/ |title=Grandfather walks 91 laps around bungalow on 91st birthday to raise cash for NHS|publisher=Shropshire Star|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-52333077/coronavirus-capt-tom-moore-inspires-91-year-old-s-walk-for-nhs|title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore inspires 91-year-old's walk for NHS |publisher=BBC News |date=17 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMoore married Pamela in 1968,<ref name=\"Lavender\">{{cite news |last1=Lavender |first1=Jane |title=Captain Tom Moore had 'given up on love' before he met beloved late wife aged 50 |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/captain-tom-moore-given-up-21876074 |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=mirror |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> and they had two daughters.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> Pamela died circa 2006.<ref name=\"Lavender\" /> He has lived with one of his daughters, Hannah, her husband, and two grandchildren, in [[Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]] since 2008.<ref name=\"BBC-52278746\" /> He also has two other grandchildren.<ref name=\"Brown\" /> In recent years he has received treatment from the NHS for skin cancer and, in 2018, a broken hip.<ref name=\"Brown\" /><ref name=\"Low\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/captain-tom-moore-99-walks-to-raise-millions-for-the-nhs-fzpn0cjfb|title=Captain Tom Moore, 99, raises \u00a35m for NHS with 100th birthday walk|first=Valentine|last=Low|accessdate=15 April 2020|work=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/99-year-old-army-veteran-raises-2-million-charity-walking-his-backyard-1497742|title=99-year-old army veteran raises $2 million for charity by walking in his backyard|first=Khaleda | last=Rahman|date=14 April 2020|website=Newsweek|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spary\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/world/war-veteran-raises-millions-garden-scli-intl-gbr/index.html|title=War veteran, 99, raises \u00a36 million by walking laps of his garden|first=Sara |last=Spary|website=CNN|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs Moore's fund-raising page]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{YouTube|wUP-ty-Tj5E|You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52316856 Captain Tom Moore: How the war veteran captured our hearts] \u2013 BBC news\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Tom}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Duke of Wellington's Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:English civil engineers]]\n[[Category:People from Keighley]]\n[[Category:Skin cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Royal Armoured Corps officers]]\n[[Category:English motorcycle racers]]\n", "name_user": "Pigsonthewing", "label": "safe", "comment": "c", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Moore_(fundraiser)"}
{"title_page": "Racing wheel", "text_new": "{{short description|Video game controller}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=August 2009}}\n[[File:EB Games Expo 2015 - Forza Motorsport 6.JPG|thumb|right|A race of ''[[Forza Motorsport 6]]'', utilizing a racing wheel controller, at the [[EB Games Expo 2015]].]]\nA '''racing wheel''' is a method of control for use in [[racing video game]]s, [[Sim racing|racing simulators]], and [[driving simulator]]s. They are usually packaged with a large [[Paddle (game controller)|paddle]] styled as a [[steering wheel]], along with a set of pedals for gas, brake, and sometimes [[clutch]] actuation, as well as various shifter controls. An [[Analog Signal|analog]] wheel and pedal set such as this allows the user to accurately manipulate steering angle and pedal control that is required to properly manage a simulated car, as opposed to digital control such as a keyboard. The relatively large range of motion further allows the user to more accurately apply the controls. Racing wheels have been developed for use with [[arcade game]]s, [[game console]]s, [[personal computer]]s, and also for professional driving simulators for race drivers.\n\n==Force feedback==\nRacing wheels started off as simple plastic wheels hooked up to a rotary potentiometer, which were sprung by springs or bungees. Eventually manufacturers began to use electric motors in the controllers, in place of springs, in order to achieve a level of [[Haptic technology|force feedback]], first seen in Microsoft's Sidewinder wheel. At first this technology simply provided the centering force and other artificial effects such as shaking the wheel in a crash or other vibrations. However, as driving simulations have evolved, their physics engines have become more accurate and the developers have linked their in-game physics more closely to the force feedback. This allows the user to truly feel what forces go through the steering rack, instead of just artificial effects, and genuinely enhance the realism of the game. Despite this, some high end manufacturers believe that force feedback has still not been perfected, and therefore companies such as Thomas SuperWheel have not adopted a force feedback system in their products. Frex, on the other hand, has gone the other way and equips their high-end Simwheel with powerful force feedback and no mechanical centering device. CEO of Fanatec Chase Johnston Explained how a wheel with no Force Feedback is very hard to use.\n\n==Comparison of racing wheels==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" cellpadding=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center; width:auto;\"\n|-\n!  Manufacturer\n!  Product\n!  Max Rotation (Deg)\n!  FFB*\n!  Clutch\n!  Shifter\n!  Brake Sensor\n!  Pedal Type\n|-\n!  Atomic\n|  Lamborghini Gallardo Evo Racing Wheel\n|  270\n|  {{no}}\n|  {{no}}\n|  Paddles\n|  Potentiometer\n|  Standing\n|-\n!  [[Logitech]]\n|  [[Logitech G920|G920]]\n|  900\n|  {{yes}}\n|  {{yes}}\n|  Paddles, H-shift\n|  Potentiometer\n|  Standing\n|-\n!  [[Logitech]]\n|  [[Logitech G29|G29]]\n|  900\n|  {{yes}}\n|  {{yes}}\n|  Paddles, H-shift\n|  Potentiometer\n|  Standing\n|-\n!  [[Logitech]]\n|  [[Logitech G27|G27]]\n|  900\n|  {{yes}}\n|  {{yes}}\n|  Paddles, H-shift\n|  Potentiometer\n|  Standing\n|-\n!  [[Logitech]]\n|  [[Logitech G25|G25]]\n|  900\n|  {{yes}}\n|  {{yes}}\n|  Paddles, H-shift, Sequential\n|  Potentiometer\n|  Standing\n|-\n!  [[Logitech]]\n|  MOMO Racing Force\n|  240\n|  {{yes}}\n|  {{no}}\n|  Paddles, Sequential\n|  Potentiometer\n|  Standing\n|-\n!  [[Logitech]]\n|  Driving Force Pro\n|  900\n|  {{yes}}\n|  {{no}}\n|  Paddles, Sequential\n|  Potentiometer\n|  Standing\n|-\n!  [[Logitech]]\n|  [[Logitech Driving Force GT|Driving Force GT]]\n|  900\n|  {{yes}}\n|  {{no}}\n|  Paddles, Sequential\n|  Potentiometer\n|  Standing\n|-\n!  [[Logitech]]\n|  MOMO Force (Red MOMO)\n|  270\n|  {{yes}}\n|  {{no}}\n|  Paddles\n|  Potentiometer\n|  Standing\n|-\n!  [[Logitech]]\n|  [[Formula Force]]\n|  180\n|  {{yes}}\n|  {{no}}\n|  